<TEXT>
the film coming to america the subject 
of a lawsuit by columnist art buchwald is at least 17 million in 
the red although it grossed 125 million paramount pictures says 
preliminary accounting of the 1988 eddie murphy comedy was 
released tuesday as part of buchwalds lawsuit against the studio 
which claimed the movie was based on a concept he created 
a superior court judge ruled in january that buchwald and 
partner alain bernheim are entitled to 250000 plus 19 percent of 
the films net profits 
under accounting by paramount which is appealing the decision 
the film has no net profits 
buchwald says he is entitled to be paid under a contract he 
signed with paramount paramount says similarities between 
buchwalds idea and the actual film were only coincidental 
pierce odonnell an attorney representing buchwald called 
paramounts financial report misleading 
the net profit system in hollywood is a scam he said the 
only question is whether its legal 
odonnell could not dispute however that the film was still 
showing a deficit according to his accounting though coming to 
america is 112 million short of turning a net profit 
paramount said that as of last dec 31 the film has brought the 
studio 125 million in gross receipts which includes film rentals 
pay television deals and videocassette sales the studio deducted 
42 million in distribution fees leaving 83 million 
the studio then claimed an additional 36 million in 
distribution expenses leaving 47 million murphy and director 
john landis who were compensated based on a percentage of the 
films gross receipts were paid 11 million combined reducing the 
films take to 36 million 
from that 36 million paramount deducted the cost of making the 
film estimated at 48 million and interest expense of between 5 
million and 6 million placing the net loss between 17 million 
and 18 million 
when some partners make profits and others are told they have 
an 18 million loss something is rotten in hollywood odonnell 
said 
said paramount attorney chuck diamond the numbers speak for 
themselves were 1718 million away from breaking even 
</TEXT>
