<TEXT>
the communistdominated legislature 
wednesday elected a new president and nominated a new prime 
minister key demands of prodemocracy protesters 
but a government official said a draft constitutional amendment 
and a new election law under consideration by the legislature will 
contain no mention of opposition parties and the issue was still 
in the cooking pot 
the new leaders are relatively unknown politicians and there was 
no immediate comment from the nations halfdozen opposition groups 
but in the past the opposition has accused the leadership of 
shuffling communist party and government posts as a cosmetic 
gesture and of stalling on providing legal guarantees for free and 
democratic elections 
the government official who spoke on condition of anonymity 
said the proposed constitutional ammendment will state that 
mongolians may only join parties that correspond to the national 
interest and solidarity 
opposition activists said in preliminary talks with the 
government both sides had agreed that the constitution would permit 
a citizen to freely choose which party he will belong to 
the 370seat legislature the great peoples hural began its 
annual session wednesday and elected as president punsaomaabiin 
ochirbat a minister of economic relations and supply since 1988 
the government official said ochirbat had initiated a policy 
over the past few years of seeking ties with countries outside the 
soviet bloc mongolia wedged between the soviet union and china 
has been a soviet satellite since 1921 
ochirbat replaces jambyn batmonh 64 who resigned last week as 
communist party chief and this week as president 
opposition parties held a rally tuesday to demand that batmonh 
stay on as president they described him as an honest man who could 
be trusted to lead mongolia until direct elections were held for a 
new president 
ochirbat 61 is a former teacher who spent the past two years 
in czechoslovakia editing the world marxist review he was not in 
the country when most of the large prodemocracy demonstrations 
were held 
he had previously served as chairman of the trade union 
congress but was ousted in 1982 by mongolias former hardline 
communist leader 
the legislature also accepted the resignation of prime minister 
dumaagiyn sodman and nominated as his successor sharavyn 
gunjaadorg 54 minister of agricuture 
</TEXT>
