<TEXT>
activists say arrests and other forms of 
intimidation have left cubas human rights movement more 
demoralized than at any time in years 
in one recent sevenday period 11 rights activists were 
arrested and the homes of two others were the scene of mass protest 
demonstrations by government supporters 
most of those arrested had expressed support for a usled 
resolution on cuba approved march 6 by the un human rights 
commission in geneva 
official anxiety is on the increase as a result of cubas 
growing international isolation and concern that steady economic 
decline could quicken 
the government seems intent on not allowing rights activists to 
cultivate possible supporters 
president fidel castro has sworn not to emulate the reforms 
being carried out in eastern europe and the soviet union 
schoolchildren have been taught to chant socialism or death 
the new national slogan that sums up castros determination to 
stick to his marxist path 
castro has always maintained that the revolutions human rights 
record is second to none pointing to advances in education health 
services and employment opportunities 
cubas children may have the highest literacy rate and lowest 
infant mortality rate in the third world castro says he believes 
a return to capitalism could wipe out these gains 
castro claims cuban dissidents are few in number and are less 
interested in promoting political freedom than in creating 
conditions for a us invasion of the island 
rights groups ridicule that suggestion 
on the morning of march 5 a meeting of rights activists was 
held at the home of sebastian arcos a movement leader according 
to official claims hundreds of outraged neighbors gathered outside 
to protest the meeting 
arcos brother gustavo says hes convinced the government 
organized the demonstration citing a similar incident at his own 
home three days later when rights activists again convened 
when a crowd of progovernment demonstrators formed at noon 
outside in protest gustavo arcos found his telephone suddenly no 
longer worked 
although the demonstrators insisted the protest was spontaneous 
gustavo arcos pointed to the instant deployment of television 
equipment and a loudspeaker suggesting the facilities had been 
prespositioned the demonstration lasted into the evening and 
featured raised fists revolutionary chants and throwing stones at 
arcos apartment windows were broken 
the cuban media approvingly called the demonstrations acts of 
repudiation 
gustavo arcos says the government now sees itself as isolated 
and vulnerable their policy is to maintain constant tension 
the rules of the game have changed they are not going to 
permit any more dissidents he said 
gustavo arcos a onetime castro confidant has spent 12 years 
in prison since the revolution began he and his allies recall with 
nostalgia the period in 1988 when they were allowed to operate with 
a minimum of harassment 
two days after the demonstration outside his home police 
arrested two wellknown rights militants samuel martinez lara and 
tania diaz castro as part of a crackdown that led to the arrests 
of six others the same day 
martinez lara is president of the pro human rights party and had 
been set free just 17 days earlier after 10 months detention 
after his rearrest the government took into custody three lay 
catholic rights militants 
the state department view is that repression in cuba has 
worsened significantly since a un human rights delegation 
visited the island in september 1988 
department figures show more than 60 activists were arrested and 
detained since then cuba insists the detentions are not based on 
political activities 
in the midst of the crackdown this month the un human rights 
commission approved by 1712 a ussponsored proposal calling 
attention to cubas rights situation 
castro reacted angrily to the resolution particularly to the 
support shown by four former warsaw pact allies hungary 
czechoslovakia poland and bulgaria 
afterward castro asked whats left of socialism what can be 
left with that repugnant conduct 
</TEXT>
