<DOCNO> AP900321-0008 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
two volumes of letters from simone de beauvoir to 
her lifetime companion jeanpaul sartre provide graphic details 
on the famous couples private life and critics say the french 
feminist philosopher emerges as predatory opportunistic and macho 
lettres a sartre letters to sartre published in 
february by gallimard along with de beauvoirs journal de 
guerre war journal recount in the most minute detail the 
daily routine of the author of the second sex the bible of 
feminists around the world 
the letters are responses to sartres own letters to de 
beauvoir which were published in 1983 as lettres au castor 
the title sartres favorite term of endearment for de beauvoir 
beaver 
her correspondence was thought to have been lost until the 
couples adopted daughter sylvie le bon de beauvoir found the 
letters by chance in a closet still wrapped in their original 
envelopes addressed to monsieur sartre or soldier sartre 
some french critics wish the letters had stayed in the closet 
this asphyxiating outpouring is a crime against the castor 
wrote marianne alphant in the daily liberation 
what do the letters teach us she asks that the pioneer 
of feminism only liked women she could dominate that this austere 
muse was as moody and jealous as a simple housewife that the 
novelist so thrilled with her little inventions was only a master 
recycler 
the letters also prove alphant wrote that de beauvoirs 
successful autobiography la force dage was rigged and full 
of falsifications 
other critics were less harsh josyane savigneau of le monde 
argued that the letters show how the couple respected the 
contract of transparency complete honesty at all costs 
which became their credo in 1929 and endured until sartres death 
in 1980 
in the letters de beauvoir details her love affairs with a male 
student of sartres and with some of her own women students 
including louise vedrine and nathalie sorokine 
hoping to add a little spice to sartres dull life as a 
german prisoner of war in 193940 she provides graphic and 
sometimes sordid details about what her lovers wore what they 
said how they behaved in bed and even how they smelled 
in bed vedrine throws herself passionately in my arms these 
sensual swoonings seem so terribly organic de beauvoir wrote 
when i wake up i feel like a fat sated man because i avoid 
caresses i think only about breakfast and about my work 
de beauvoir wrote that sex was a chore yet she was fascinated 
with brothels prostitutes and other forms of low life that her 
buttonedup bourgeois upbringing had made taboo 
at times she comes across as downright conniving if wanda 
says anything about me be sure to tell me so i can know if my 
charm offensive is working she wrote 
for alphant de beauvoirs behavior towards women was predator 
and macho linked to an ambiguous desire to play the role of the 
man 
but she was equally aggressive with men something extremely 
pleasant has happened to me something i never expected i slept 
with the little bost three days ago naturally i was the one to 
suggest it she wrote to sartre in 1938 bosts first name was 
not given 
im very fond of him we spend idyllic days and passionate 
nights together the relationship is something precious and 
strong but superficial too and easy just an agreeable 
fulfillment of relations that had always been pleasant 
nonetheless the overriding theme in the letters is de 
beauvoirs undying love and respect for sartre she addresses him 
as my dear little being and she loves everything about him 
from his little arm and little lip to his little 
roundneck pullover sweaters and little face 
when im with you nothing seems so terrible as leaving you 
yet faraway the least little fear is unbearable i love you 
passionately im empty and unhappy without you i love you 
with something tragic and with complete abandonment she wrote 
le bon de beauvoir justified publishing the letters she said 
the whole truth regardless of how shocking or unsettling is 
better than myths and part truths 
isnt it preferable to say everything in order to reveal the 
truth and avoid by the force of first person narrative all the 
cliches myths lies and allow the real person in all its 
entirety to emerge le bon de beauvoir wrote in the preface 
readers may be surprised to learn how little de beauvoir worried 
about or even thought about world war ii she was too busy rushing 
from one left bank cafe to another meeting friends and lovers 
analyzing their relationships and writing it all in letters to 
sartre all in the name of honesty 
from a distance this was a grand task alphant concluded 
up close it looks more like a hamster running on a wheel 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

