<TEXT>
when you talk about recycling paper in the world 
trade center youre talking about saving forests its landlord 
says 
nearly 100000 trees a year could be saved in a new recycling 
program for the giant office complex according to stephen berger 
executive director of the port authority of new york and new 
jersey which operates the center 
initially 10000 of the 60000 people in its offices will be 
asked to recycle paper at their own desks berger said tuesday 
the program ultimately could involve every desk worker in the two 
110story towers and the five other buildings of the trade center 
the center generates 65 tons of garbage every day of which 
about 37 tons is wastepaper berger said 
if 60 percent of that wastepaper were recycled we could 
recapture 225 tons of paper a day he said thats more than 
10 times our current total 
according to one estimate it would be equivalent to a daily 
saving of 383 trees said berger or more than 95000 a year 
based on 250 working days 
the daily savings also would include the 157000 gallons of 
water and 92000 kilowatts of electricity it takes to produce that 
amount of new paper and the 67 cubic yards of landfill space it 
would take to bury it 
in the new program each person will have a recycling bin 
besides a regular wastebasket and cull used stationery copy 
machine paper computer printout computer cards note paper and 
glossy paper from the rest of the trash 
each floor of the center also will have designated sites for 
discarding newspapers 
the port authority said it also is replacing colored message 
pads and yellow legal pads with recycled and recyclable whitepaper 
versions 
