the state senate on wednesday overwhelmingly 
approved an expansion of new yorks shield law that would protect 
virtually any information gathered by reporters or photographers 
the bill ensures that reporters notes unused video or audio 
tapes and newsroom files cant be subpoenaed unless its proven the 
information is necessary to a criminal case and couldnt be 
obtained elsewhere 
the bill which passed the senate 475 and was approved by the 
state assembly two months ago is expected to be signed by gov 
mario cuomo 
the bills sponsor republican sen roy goodman said it would 
prevent the press from being hauled into court on fishing 
expeditions by defense attorneys 
it will recognize particularly in criminal cases that the 
press should not be made to be an investigative arm of the 
government goodman said 
state sen emanuel gold a democrat who led opposition to the 
proposal said the press has as much an obligation to participate 
in trials as any other citizen he likened the subpoena of notes to 
jury duty 
i dont think theres a newspaper in the world that doesnt 
preach in favor of good citizenship gold said it seems in 
some situations the newspapers cant be bothered by the 
requirements of good citizenship 
state law only protects information obtained by reporters in 
confidence the legislation approved wednesday puts the force of 
law behind a 1988 state court of appeals decision that found 
nonconfidential information would have to be disclosed if it is 
relevant and the reporter is the only available source 
the same bill failed by two votes in the final day of the 1989 
legislative session gold who filibustered on the legislation in 
