communist party they ousted it will have 12 seats in the 
400member parliament 
the coalitions showing was largely anticipated in recent weeks 
after hardline communist leader erich honecker was forced out on 
oct 18 by massive protests activists spoke of a third way 
between capitalism and communism of governing east germany with a 
new form of democratic socialism 
but the cry for reunification with west germany quickly 
dominated the protest movement 
michael kukuntz one of the founders of the most prominent 
revolutionary group new forum said the opening of the berlin wall 
in november effectively transformed the revolt against dictatorial 
rule into a clamor for consumer goods 
the air began rushing out of his movement he calls my child 
on the night the wall was opened he said east germans who now had 
free access to west germany migrated by the thousands daily and 
those who went west only to visit brought back images of a parallel 
world of wealthy germans 
new forum formed a shoestring political party with two other 
dissident groups democracy now and the initiative for peace and 
freedom 
kukuntz acknowledged that there were differences within new 
forum over whether to embrace reunification and that the groups 
position remained vague in the months before the vote 
meanwhile the wellheeled alliance led by the christian 
democratic union and backed by west german chancellor helmut kohl 
promised rapid unification it won with 48 percent of the vote 
the social democrats who were backed by the west german social 
democrats and favored a slower pace for unification finished 
second 
its not a victory for the christian democrats its not a 
victory for kohl its a victory for the deutsche mark said 
michael bartoszek who helped organize the new democracy dissident 
group in september 
the members of our movement were the first to fight for 
democracy he said 
kukuntz 39 a graphic designer said he began dissident 
activity in the early 1980s his wife was arrested for taking part 
in a group called women for peace and fired from her job 
miss gastmann was working in a staterun exportimport office 
when she said she was drawn into the protest movement in september 
she said she took part in demonstrations at the gethsemane 
evangelical church in east berlin holding candlelight protest 
vigils with thousands of others 
she said she was among hundreds authorities arrested following 
an oct 7 rally at the church and was held for 24 hours in a small 
cell with 20 other women she said she saw police beat some of 
those women 
when the hardline communists fell less than two weeks later and 
the selfstyled communist reformers who replaced them agreed to new 
elections miss gastmann began working as a bookkeeper with the 
initiative for peace and freedom 
i was very sad after the elections because the people of the 
christian democratic union are not the people of the 
revolution she said i cant understand why the people of east 
germany cant see that 
while a solidarity activist leads poland and a former dissident 
is president of czechoslovakia the east german revolutionaries say 
they will continue to fill the role that is most familiar to them 
we started as the opposition and now we are the opposition 
once more said bartoszek 
