<TEXT>
nasa will talk with aerospace company 
officials thursday about sending astronauts to rescue a 157 
million communications satellite stranded in space by a miswired 
titan 3 rocket 
the intelsat 6 satellite is whirling around earth at an altitude 
of 276 miles about 22000 miles lower than it should be to do its 
job 
the design was wrong said judy stowell a spokeswoman for 
martin marietta corp which built the rocket our analysis shows 
an engineering design error caused the vehicle to be wired 
improperly 
as a result after the titan was launched on march 14 the 
satellite didnt separate automatically as it was supposed to when 
engineers sent a separation signal a small rocket that was to 
boost the satellite to its duty station stayed with the spent titan 
and left the satellite marooned 
a martin marietta spokesman was quoted by the denver post as 
saying that the titan had been wired to launch two satellites and 
that the separation signal went to a location where there was none 
but ms stowell said tuesday that explanation was premature and 
that two committees were investigating the failure 
while martin marietta searched for the cause the national 
aeronautics and space administration scheduled its meeting at the 
johnson space center in houston with representatives of intelsat 
owner of the satellite and hughes aircraft its builder 
intelsat a 118nation consortium did not insure the satellite 
which was to have gone into service over the atlantic ocean a 
spokesman tony trujillo said it was the most sophisticated 
communications satellite ever built capable of carrying 120000 
telephone calls simultaneously 
intelsat was being charged 115 million for the titan rocket and 
launch by martin marietta the satellite cost an additional 157 
million 
nasa hasnt said whether it is willing to go after the 
satellite as it has for five others 
they are just going to come in and give us some information 
where the spacecraft is and its condition and so forth said hal 
lambert manager of integration operations at the space center 
we are going to discuss whether its possible to get the 
satellite 
two rescue methods have been proposed lambert said in one the 
space shuttle would carry a rocket stage into orbit to be bolted 
onto the satellite by astronauts in the other the satellite would 
be put into the shuttle cargo bay and brought back to earth for 
refitting 
because it was not intended for shuttle operations the fiveton 
satellite has no fitting that could be grappled by the shuttles 
robot arm that would mean a special capture device would have to 
be designed and built 
industry sources have little doubt the rescue can be 
accomplished astronauts have saved five satellites that way 
bringing three home and repairing two in orbit 
the cost of such a mission however would be high and probably 
would become the deciding factor with shuttle flights costing 250 
million and up nasa no longer will rescue satellites for 15 
million as it did in 1984 with the palapa and westar satellites 
nasa spokesman say they dont know how much would be charged 
today because the agency no longer does commercial business and 
there is no published rate schedule the charges however probably 
would be based on the amount of cargo space and weight involved 
a virginia company orbital sciences corp has a device called 
a transfer orbit stage that includes a duplicate of the rocket that 
was to carry the intelsat satellite to its high orbit 
joseph padavano chief engineer of the device said it would 
take up only onefifth of the shuttle cargo space but that it 
weighs 25000 pounds more than half of the shuttles capacity 
 
