<TEXT>
an informal survey of new york city abortion 
providers suggests that women who reveal they are infected with the 
aids virus may quickly find their appointments canceled 
twothirds of the abortion clinics and physicians surveyed by 
the citys human rights commission canceled an appointment after 
the caller said she was infected with the human immunodeficiency 
virus or hiv which causes aids 
revealing your hiv status to a health care person is not 
safe katherine franke a commission lawyer who led the study 
said tuesday 
most people dont tell thats the way they get abortions 
she said 
the commission began looking into the matter after receiving 
several reports from women who claimed they had been denied 
abortion services because they were hivpositive 
physicians and representatives with aids organizations and 
abortion groups said they were unaware of any other study that has 
documented the problem in other parts of the country although they 
had heard anecdotal reports 
dr lewis koplik an albuquerque nm 
obstetriciangynecologist who heads the national abortion 
federations medical advisory committee said he has an 
undocumented gut feeling that the new york experience may be 
occurring elsewhere 
if you have one woman who has hiv infection or aids and cant 
get service thats a real problem its just something that should 
not happen he said 
los angeles obstetriciangynecologist david grimes chairman of 
planned parenthoods medical advisory committee said he does not 
believe the problem is widespread although it may be more apparent 
on the east coast where more women are infected with hiv 
he did say he often sees patients referred by other physicians 
who feel inadequately prepared to treat hivinfected women 
women who are hivpositive but have no symptoms of aids and no 
other diseases are generally at no greater risk than nonhiv women 
for abortion grimes said but he said women whose immune systems 
are compromised whether by aids or some other disease are more 
appropriately treated in a hospital 
in the survey conducted from november 1988 through february 
1989 callers from the new york city human rights commission made 
appointments with 30 abortion clinics and physicians that 
advertised in the yellow pages twenty canceled the appointment 
after the caller said she was infected with hiv but had no symptoms 
of aids 
twelve of the 20 said they did not have adequate infection 
control while others said abortion on an hivinfected woman was 
too complicated a procedure for them to handle and referred the 
caller to a hospital 
many of the responses were very hostile ms franke said 
some just hung up or said we cant treat your kind 
for women refused services or referred to a crowded public 
hospital the result may be delay in getting an abortion which 
increases chances of complications ms franke said 
the chances that a woman will pass the aids virus to her baby 
are estimated at between 20 percent and 50 percent 
franke said that while the human rights commission would be 
prepared to file suit against clinics that refuse to serve women 
with hiv it would rather see the problem addressed through 
education of physicians and other health professionals 
public health officials believe that about 1 million people in 
the united states are infected with the aids virus more than 
11000 of the 121645 cases of aids in us adults reported since 
june 1 1981 have been women 
