<TEXT>
china today acnowledged severe economic problems 
but included in its 1990 budget steep spending increases for 
defense education and subsidies for inefficient staterun 
enterprises 
the present financial situation remains grave with many 
contradictions and great difficulties cropping up in national 
finance finance minister wang bingqian told the national 
legislature 
the communist nations economic downturn following 18 months of 
austerity measures has reduced revenues and complicated efforts to 
meet demands to balance the budget he said 
what is more in some localities and work units financial 
procedures became chaotic supervision and management became lax 
budgetary control was loosened and tax evasion illegal retention 
of profits diversion of funds and similar breaches of financial 
laws and discipline became quite common he said 
he told the 2700 delegates to the annual national peoples 
congress that china would register a deficit of 189 billion down 
slightly from 2 billion in 1989 if tabulated by western 
accounting methods in which domestic and foreign borrowing are 
regarded as part of the deficit the imbalance would be 9 billion 
an increase of more than 1 billion 
wang put state revenues for 1990 at 6886 billion up 109 
percent and spending at 7075 billion up 103 percent 
while most departments were being told to cut spending and 
practice frugality again this year the resurgent military with 
more political clout following its role in putting down 
prodemocracy demonstrations in june was awarded a sizable 
increase 
national defense was budgeted 616 billion an increase of 152 
percent over 1989 western military analysts say real spending is 
far greater if peripheral costs are counted 
spending on education in a nation with a 20 percent illiteracy 
rate was increased 98 percent to 75 billion 
nearly onethird of the state budget 226 billion will go to 
subsidies for moneylosing enterprises and price rises a great 
drain on the state treasury wang said 
the state in 1990 will need 14 billion to support moneylosing 
state businesses up from 1277 billion last year 
wang said the state which last year required most workers and 
factories to buy bonds to help finance public debt has budgeted 
26 billion to pay back individuals up 2 billion 
however amortization of bonds held by enterprises public 
institutions and banks will be postponed he said 
wang said the government will try to increase revenues by 
raising business tax rates and improving collection of individual 
earnings taxes 
he said beijing will also moderately increase the revenues 
local authorities must turn over to the state and reduce subsidies 
to some localities 
in another speech to the congress state planning commission 
chief zou jiahua said china needed more central controls over the 
economy saying the state will set more mandatory targets this year 
for basic materials in short supply and exert more controls over 
distribution of goods and capital investment 
