senior leader deng xiaoping today officially left 
his last government post the chairmanship of the state central 
military commission 
the expected move followed the 85yearold dengs retirement in 
november from the central military commission of the ruling 
communist party a body with largely the same composition and 
function as the government commission 
that was his last party position 
deng who came to power in the late 1970s and began 
marketoriented economic reforms that have changed the face of 
china is still regarded as the nations most powerful man 
he played an instrumental role in the revival of ideological 
orthodoxy following the suppression of the prodemocracy movement 
in june 
although he now holds no party or government posts he is 
believed to still have the final say on major decisions and plays a 
key role in maintaining the outward impression of harmony among 
beijings various leadership factions 
deng has sought to set an example for other aging 
revolutionaries by stepping down from public office and encouraging 
the promotion of younger leaders he resigned from the politburo 
standing committee the partys top decisionmaking body in late 
1987 
however he and other more conservative octogenarians have not 
relinquished their behindthescenes authority 
deng was not present at todays session of the national peoples 
congress which accepted his resignation and did not attend 
tuesdays opening of the annual meeting 
the congress acted on a letter from the party central committee 
saying that deng had resigned from the party military commission 
and proposing that he also be allowed to give up the chairmanship 
of the state body 
