the dollar rose against most major foreign 
currencies in early european trading today while the british pound 
plummeted on the heels of tuesdays budget 
gold prices were sharply lower falling by as much as 9 an 
ounce the lowest level since late last year 
the bank of england reportedly intervened to stop the pounds 
slide which began minutes after foreign exchange markets opened in 
london 
currency dealers said chancellor of the exchequer john majors 
first budget delivered to parliament on tuesday was too soft on 
inflation and increased pressure for another rise in interest rates 
it is not a happy outlook said tim potter a senior dealer 
at goldman sachs international in london 
the dollar gained support from several international events 
dealers said including concerns about soviet troop movements along 
the lithuanian border and fears that the cost of german unification 
will be far greater than expected 
the dollar was also perked up by tuesdays release of a 
relatively good us trade report for january traders said 
