<TEXT>
president lee tenghui has risen from 
obscurity to become a widely popular leader since succeeding the 
chiang kaishek family dynasty but he now faces intense pressure 
to bring more democracy to taiwan 
much of his twoyear tenure as president has been marked by 
cautious policies designed to strike a balance between the 
conservative old guard of the ruling nationalist party and an 
increasingly restless population clamoring for more freedoms 
a president acts like the head of a family lee recently 
said all members interests must be taken care of to keep the 
family happy and harmonious 
but newspapers recently have drawn a different picture of the 
67yearold leader saying he rarely consults party elders on 
important policy decisions 
he also displayed independence when he chose his top personal 
aide as his vice presidential candidate shunning demands by many 
old guard politicians that his running mate be the sole surviving 
son of chiang kaishek 
the move led to speculation that lee was primarily interested in 
consolidating his own power 
some people say lee could turn himself into another emperor if 
he is given too much power said nationalist lawmaker huang 
chuwen but i dont think he has any intention to do it nor 
will the society allow it 
many taiwanese hope that lee elected as president for six more 
years today will become less cautious and move to dismantle the 
existing political system that ensures the electoral college and 
legislature are controlled by old guard nationalists 
those elderly politicians were elected on mainland china before 
the nationalist government fled to taiwan after losing a civil war 
to communist forces they were frozen in office to support the 
partys claim that it remains the legitimate government of all 
china 
public pressure for general elections has increased sharply 
particularly after some deputies proposed increasing the assemblys 
powers and the salaries of its members 
