<TEXT>
the supreme court ruled today that migrant 
farm workers injured on the job may sue their employers in federal 
court after receiving workercompensation benefits 
by a 90 vote in a florida case the justices said states do not 
have the power to ban such suits 
justice thurgood marshall writing for the court rejected the 
us labor departments interpretation of a federal law designed to 
protect the seasonal workers 
the law the migrant and seasonal agricultural worker protection 
act provides aggrieved farmworkers with direct recourse to 
federal court where their rights under the statute are violated 
marshall said the labor department is not empowered to regulate 
the scope of the judicial power vested by the statute 
the court upheld a lower court victory for 10 florida farmhands 
who were hurt in 1985 while being transported in a van by their 
employer the adams fruit co 
each collected workercompensation benefits from adams under 
florida law and then sued the company in federal court alleging 
the van was unsafe 
the company said floridas workercompensation law made it the 
exclusive legal remedy for such injuries and a federal judge agreed 
but the 11th us circuit court of appeals overruled the judge 
and reinstated the workers suit 
that ruling conflicted with a decision by the 4th us circuit 
court of appeals which said a farm worker injured when sprayed by 
pesticides could not sue 
in resolving the conflict today marshall said the federal laws 
enforcement provisions in no way intimate that the availability 
of the right to sue in federal court is affected by state 
workers compensation law 
state officials from california texas and massachusetts urged 
the high court to rule in favor of the migrant workers 
the case is adams fruit vs barrett 882035 
</TEXT>
