also on trial is saudi financier adnan khashoggi accused of 
helping mrs marcos and her late husband philippines president 
ferdinand e marcos conceal their ownership of the real estate 
marcos was named in the october 1988 indictment but died sept 
28 in exile in hawaii 
mrs marcos wearing a black dress and a mournful expression 
told the mob of reporters who met her tuesday that she was unhappy 
over facing trial here i should be tried in my own country the 
republic of the philippines not in a foreign country she said 
supporters greeted mrs marcos with signs reading marcos is 
innocent and justice for imelda other signs showed pictures 
of the marcoses with expresidents nixon carter and reagan 
arriving separately with his lawyers khashoggi told reporters 
he felt the united states had betrayed mrs marcos but was 
too big to be embarrassed by any revelations from the trial 
asked where he might prefer to be the saudi who was once called 
the worlds richest man replied i would rather be in mecca 
fasting 
mrs marcos could face a maximum of 50 years in prison and a 1 
million fine if convicted on all counts of racketeering 
racketeering conspiracy mail fraud and obstruction of justice 
khashoggi 54 is charged with obstruction of justice and mail 
fraud which carry a maximum sentence upon conviction of 10 years 
in prison and a 500000 fine 
both defendants have pleaded innocent 
those prospective jurors not dismissed for such reasons as work 
obligations or personal bias were told to return to court next 
tuesday when the final panel is to be chosen the trial is expected 
to last three to four months 
asked what they knew of mrs marcos several prospective jurors 
said they had heard about the many pairs of shoes she left behind 
when she and her husband fled the phillipines in early 1986 and 
went into exile in hawaii 
critics of the marcoses including the government of president 
corazon aquino have cited the shoes as symbolizing the excesses of 
an opulent lifestyle of leaders in a country plagued by widespread 
poverty 
samuel cerezo a 51yearold transit official was asked whether 
the shoes would prejudice him against mrs marcos 
no my daughter also has a lot of shoes he replied 
