<TEXT>
states may not prohibit grand jury witnesses 
from ever revealing their own testimony the supreme court ruled 
unanimously today 
the court said a florida law providing such a prohibition 
similar to laws in 15 other states violated freespeech rights 
the decision upholding a federal appeals court ruling is a 
defeat for florida officials who tried to block a former newspaper 
reporter from disclosing details of his appearance before a grand 
jury four years ago 
the interests advanced by the portion of the florida statute 
struck down are not sufficient to overcome the reporters first 
amendment right to make a truthful statement of information he 
acquired on his own chief justice william h rehnquist wrote for 
the court 
he added the ban extends not merely to the life of the grand 
jury but into the indefinite future the potential for abause of 
the florida prohibition through its employment as a device to 
silence those who know of unlawful conduct or irregularities on the 
part of public officials is apparent 
todays decision does not affect state laws barring grand jury 
witnesses from disclosing their testimony while the investigation 
is in progress 
jane kirtley of the reporters committee for freedom of the press 
said the decision will help journalists who want to interview 
people who testified before grand juries once an investigation ends 
the court recognized that this kind of statute is an 
overwhelming restraint that could not withstand constitutional 
scrutiny ms kirtley said 
michael smith a former reporter for the charlotte heraldnews 
in charlotte county fla wants to publish a news story and 
possibly a book about a 1986 grand jury investigation into 
allegations of corruption in the county sheriffs department and 
the county state attorneys office 
the grand jury probe ended in 1986 and no indictments were 
handed down 
smith challenged the florida grand jury secrecy law because he 
feared he could be prosecuted for revealing his testimony before 
the secret panel 
a federal judge upheld the law and threw out smiths suit but 
the 11th us circuit court of appeals ruled for smith sparking 
floridas appeal to the supreme court 
in his opinion for the court rehnquist cited past decisions 
that say states may not punish publication of lawfully obtained 
truthful information absent a need to further a state interest of 
the highest order 
no such need exists in this case he said 
rehnquist acknowledged that the invalidated law could help 
prevent investigation targets who later stand trial from trying to 
influence grand jury witnesses but he said with present day 
criminal procedure generally requiring the disclosure of witnesses 
on the part of the state the names of these witnesses will be 
available to the accused sometime before trial in any event 
the chief justice also noted that florida provides substantial 
criminal penalties for both perjury and tampering with witnesses 
the justices were told that the 15 states with laws similar to 
floridas are alabama arizona indiana kentucky louisiana 
michigan mississippi missouri nevada north carolina north 
dakota south dakota texas utah and washington 
the case is butterworth vs smith 881993 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
