riverboat gambling will be allowed in 
missisippi beginning april 1 under a bill signed into law by gov 
ray mabus 
proponents have touted the measure as a way to boost tourism in 
communities along the mississippi river mabus signed the bill 
tuesday 
riverboat gambling already has been approved in illinois and 
iowa but the illinois law doesnt take effect until january 1991 
and the iowa statute not until april 1991 
in mississippi boats at least 150 feet long and capable of 
carrying a minimum 250 passengers would be allowed to open casinos 
on the waterway 
the state would license the boats which could open their 
casinos while moving or docked 
the important aspect of the legislation is that it would let 
those communities along the mississippi river have the right to 
vote on whether they would like to have casinotype gambling in 
their area said the governors spokesman kevin vandebroek 
residents of mississippi counties with ports on the river could 
force a referendum and voters could forbid the boats from docking 
in their counties the mississippi river forms the states western 
line 
some operators already have expressed an interest in bringing 
gambling boats to the river 
weve been meeting with people that have shown some 
preliminary interest in bringing a boat into this area said 
jimmy heidel executive vice president of the vicksburgwarren 
chamber of commerce 
cruise ships can already open their casinos while in the waters 
of the mississippi sound off the states southern coast 
mississippi lawmakers are trying to resolve differences in a bill 
that would reduce the minimum size of those vessels 
