march 19 
san antonio expressnews on subsidies to the national rifle 
association 
not many people are aware that the defense department indirectly 
subsidizes the national rifle association or nra the 
multimilliondollar handout is drawing the attention it deserves as 
the pentagon adjusts to a shrinking share of the federal budget 
the subsidy comes from the armys division of civilian 
marksmanship or dcm which was established in 1903 to improve the 
shooting skills among men of military age the program received 
46 million in fiscal 1990 the bush budget for fiscal 1991 asks 
for 56 million 
only about 200 marksmen were recruited last year for the 
military as a result of dcms efforts that works out to about 
23000 per recruit which the house armed services committee calls 
a very expensive recruiting tool 
us rep fortney stark dcalif isnt the first to question 
the value of the program expresident jimmy carter tried to do 
away with it and a federal judge once suggested that the 
symbolic relationship between the army and the nra might be 
unhealthy since the nra attempts to influence the government on 
controversial issues such as gun control 
thousands of small items could be cut from the budget without 
impairing us interests the armys nraoriented marksmanship 
program is one of them 
