<TEXT>
former president reagan does not have to 
produce some three dozen diary entries requested by john poindexter 
for his irancontra trial a federal judge ruled today 
us district court judge harold greene said that production of 
the diary entries is not essential to the achievement of justice 
in this case 
the judges ruling came as reagans videotaped testimony was 
being shown at poindexters trial on five felony charges of 
conspiracy making false statements and obstructing congress 
greene earlier had directed reagan to turn over the diary 
entries to his former national security adviser but the 
expresident challenged the judges order by invoking executive 
privilege the bush administration joined reagans assertion of the 
privilege 
the claims of executive privilege filed on behalf of the 
former president and of the incumbent president are sufficient to 
defeat poindexters request said greene 
greene granted reagans motion to quash poindexters subpoena 
for the diary entries which relate to both the iran initiative and 
contra resupply operation 
the judge said there is absolutely no basis in law for a 
holding that poindexter is entitled to the diary entries in 
addition to reagans videotaped testimony 
poindexters lawyers say he needs the diaries because reagan was 
unable in his videotaped testimony to recall many details of the 
irancontra affair for example the former president said he could 
not remember when he learned of a november 1985 shipment of hawk 
missiles to iran 
mr reagan did testify under oath at great length about many 
specific activities in his administration an event that is 
unprecedented in american history said greene 
the judge said reagans testimony plus written answers he gave 
several years ago in the irancontra affair provided poindexter 
with ample assistance for the conduct of his defense 
poindexters lawyers say the diaries may refer to facts that 
reagan now says he cannot recall 
but if the concept of executive privilege is to retain any 
meaning it will surely shield personal presidential papers from 
production on so flimsy a basis said greene 
in greenes courtroom meanwhile jurors began watching reagans 
videotaped testimony taken feb 1617 in los angeles for the 
poindexter trial 
the jurors were instructed to treat his testimony like that of 
any other witness 
greene said testimony from reagan should not be judged by a 
different standard you apply the same test he told the jurors 
you give the same care and same weight to reagans 
videotaped testimony as you would if he were here in person 
greene told the jury of seven women and five men 
poindexters lawyers were presenting the reagan tape in a bid to 
offset evidence presented by irancontra prosecutors who brought 
their case to a close tuesday 
would you please state your full name and spell your last name 
for the record a clerk asked on the videotape 
ronald reagan reagan the former president responded 
in 7 days of testimony prosecution witnesses told the jury the 
former national security adviser destroyed a presidential document 
and sent false letters to congress about covert aid to the contra 
rebels in nicaragua 
the jury was watching reagans testimony on a television monitor 
placed in front of the jury box transcripts were released the week 
after reagan testified and the tapes were shown in the federal 
courthouse in washington dc copies of the tapes were being 
released to the news media today 
reagans videotape was to be shown in its entirety concluding 
at midday thursday greene told the jury 
on tuesday greene denied a defense motion of acquittal saying 
there is evidence suggesting poindexter adopted false information 
designed to obstruct congress 
reagan made a number of statements favorable to poindexter 
he said he was convinced that his aides activities on behalf of 
the contras were all being done within the law he also said 
i dont think any false statements were made by poindexter in 
connection with the irancontra affair 
the former president said i am in complete support with 
allegedly false letters poindexter sent to congress about assisting 
the contras 
the letters said the administration was in compliance with 
both the spirit and letter of the law restricting aid to the 
rebels 
but they also embraced yearearlier denials by thennational 
security adviser robert mcfarlane that white house aide oliver 
north was raising funds for the contras and aiding them militarily 
while reagan said he never gave poindexter authority to destroy 
records or obstruct congress he did suggest it might have been all 
right to withhold information and destroy documents to protect 
national security in the us arms initiative with iran 
reagan suggested that any leaks of sensitive information from 
congress might jeopardize the lives of us hostages held in 
lebanon 
under crossexamination the former president said he never 
had any inkling his aides were guiding the contras strategy in 
any way and he said he never authorized his aides to break the 
law 
