<TEXT>
nearly a year after the exxon valdez disaster 
little has been done to protect wildlife from another such oil 
spill an expert who directed the rehabilitation of sea otters 
after the alaska spill said wednesday 
basically there are no facilities in existence today anywhere 
in north america nor any ongoing organization to respond to another 
oil spill randall w davis said in an interview 
davis codirector of international wildlife research of san 
diego calif is completing a report on the rescue program after 
the alaska spill last march 24 that includes recommendations for 
oil spill contingency planning in alaska and california 
the valdez spewed almost 11 million gallons of crude oil into 
the sea when it ran aground in prince william sound soaking 1100 
miles of scenic coastland searchers found 34400 dead birds and 
believe at least 1000 sea otters and countless other animals died 
in the nations worst oil spill 
we are only a little bit further ahead than we were a year ago 
in that we have a little bit better understanding of how to do it 
but so far there has been very little advance preparation davis 
said 
in order to respond quickly that is within one day we need a 
rehabilitaion facility he said we probably need a number of 
them in areas that are considered high risk 
davis said these areas should include valdez the southern 
terminal of the alaska oil pipeline and probably a site on the 
california coast and others in other parts of the country 
the special needs of marine mammals make a facility much more 
difficult to build he said birds are a little bit easier to 
treat marine mammals require generally more sophisticated 
facilities and it is difficult to build them right at the time of 
the spill 
our response in alaska was not as effective as it could have 
been because we were trying to build those specialized facilities 
while we were treating animals said davis that makes it very 
very difficult 
international wildlife research has drawn up plans for a 
combined rehabilitation and research facility that davis said could 
be built either in california or alaska for about 5 million he 
said the rehabilitation portion alone could probably be built for 
15 million 
davis was in washington for a news conference at which the izaak 
walton league of america presented a conservation award to the 
procter amp gamble company for its support of animal rescue efforts 
the company donated manpower a computer and dawn dishwashing 
detergent to the alaska effort it also is underwriting production 
and distribution of mission rescue a video about the cleanup 
that is being offered at no charge for showings at zoos aquariums 
and nature centers 
davis oversaw the rehabilitation of 230 sea otters in the months 
following the alaska spill 
he was joined at the news conference by jay holcolmb director 
of international bird rescue research of berkeley calif who 
headed activities that saved some 1600 birds after the valdez 
spill 
by using computer technology we were able to record and save 
crucial technical data collected over a sixmonth period on the 
care of thousands of birds he said this information proved 
its worth in our work in rescue efforts following the recent spills 
in san francisco and huntington beach calif 
