<TEXT>
global warming during the past century could not 
have come solely from a longterm influence of the oceans 
according to a study that supports the idea that the greenhouse 
effect has begun to warm the earth 
a computer simulation suggests that the oceans can account for 
only about threefifths of the warming recorded in the last 100 
years 
the researchers cautioned that the result does not prove 
greenhouse warming played a role other scientists agreed but 
split on how strongly it bolsters the idea that greenhouse warming 
has begun 
the greenhouse effect refers to a warming caused by a buildup in 
the atmosphere of certain gases such as carbon dioxide chiefly 
from human activity scientists are concerned that it eventually 
could alter climates and rainfall patterns and lead to coastal 
flooding from raised ocean levels 
but they disagree about whether the greenhouse effect has yet 
produced any detectable impact 
the earth has warmed by about ninetenths of a degree fahrenheit 
during the past century a major problem in demonstrating a role 
for the greenhouse effect is that scientists do not know how much 
of the warming comes from longterm natural variability said 
gerald meehl of the national center for atmospheric research in 
boulder colo 
the oceans which slowly absorb and release huge amounts of 
heat are probably the most likely source of this longterm 
influence he said 
the new study of the oceans influence is presented in 
thursdays issue of the british journal nature by tml wigley and 
scb raper of the university of east anglia in norwich england 
their simulation found that over intervals of up to 100 years 
the oceans might produce a trend of up to about half a degree 
fahrenheit 
that means the ocean influence could not have produced the 
observed global warming by itself the researchers wrote yet we 
still cannot claim to have unequivocally detected the greenhouse 
effect they said 
researcher robert cess said the study cannot really rule out the 
idea that the oceans did produce the global warming the simulation 
was too simplified to produce a firm conclusion said cess an 
atmospheric sciences professor at the state university of new york 
at stony brook 
but researcher stephen schneider of atmospheric research center 
who called himself 80 percent certain that greenhouse warming has 
begun said the result adds to his belief 
its not proof yet he said its another step along the 
way 
scientists will need 10 to 20 more years of observations to be 
sure if they are seeing a greenhouse warming he said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

