<TEXT>
for the seven months he lived in tompkins square 
park louis hrusovsky could count the days since his last 
satisfying meal the hours spent idle the moments until police 
would roust him 
early wednesday hrusovsky returned to tompkins square and put 
that abject arithmatic to good use he counted the homeless 
this area will be one of the most thorough counts in the 
city he said i lived in this park for seven months until 
three weeks ago i can give you the name of everyone in the park 
hrusovsky and his fellow enumerators a cheery determined 
group tried to do just that they were a bright spot in the first 
national effort to count americas unsheltered 
from the start critics had said that the census conducted 
tuesday night and wednesday morning would overlook many of the 
nations homeless including an estimated 70000 to 90000 in new 
york city 
city officials and advocates for the homeless repeated the 
charges on wednesday not only did the counter miss the nooks and 
crannies where many homeless sleep subway tunnels and back 
alleys they also failed to visit several shelters 
at the port authority bus terminal home to hundreds of 
homeless reporters watched as some counters milled around a 
newsstand it seemed as if they were ignoring the terminals upper 
levels where many people sleep in hallways bus platforms and 
stairwells 
barbara everitt bryant the us census bureau director 
insisted that the terminal was blanketed and said any shelters 
that were missed would be checked on wednesday night anyway 
census officials said they were looking for a snapshot of the 
homeless not precise numbers 
among the skeptics was a man who identified himself as sharif 
he said he had been living in tompkins square park a scruffy plot 
of green on manhattans lower east side for the past four months 
the census bureau doesnt have the heart or audacity to go to 
where people crash he said before the census takers arrived he 
pointed out nooks of the park abandoned buildings and vacant lots 
where he said sleeping homeless would go uncounted 
sharif was wrong at about 230 am hrusovsky and 11 other 
enumerators arrived at the park methodically carefully they 
counted everyone 
some of the census takers had been homeless some had not all 
were from the neighborhood and knew it well 
since 1952 my family has never been in the census said 
blanca moore i chose to work in my neighborhood and i am 
hopeful that all these people can be counted 
after counting the sleeping forms dotting the park 11 
enumerators wended their way through the lettered streets that are 
known as alphabet city a decayed section of vacant lots abandoned 
buildings occupied by squatters and gentrified apartment houses 
first stop at 3 am was a fencedin lot on avenue b 
paul eskridge tested the chained gate and peered in at three 
makeshift tents ringed by old appliances and grocery carts stacked 
with cans to be returned for deposit 
this is private domain so well have to guess three tents 
two people in each to be conservative so six in all he said 
filling out the forms 
as the group made its way down ninth street eskridge darted 
across the street and snagged a man who said he was homeless 
what kind of hour is this to be out you guys are the kooks 
said the homeless man he politely answered the questions 
at the next corner the group eyed three young men standing on 
the corner 
i know those three theyre drug dealers said one 
enumerator 
ok then avoid them said another 
on a side street off avenue d the group stepped into a 
rubblestrewn lot where three shacks stood patched together from 
tar paper and wood scraps 
dont wake anyone up one woman whispered as a man emerged 
from a leanto 
hi susie garcia called out to him were from the census 
bureau 
a few minutes of explanation and the group left with the count 
nine males six females all adults 
one counter mentioned he saw a child in one shack 
theyre saying there were no kids because theyre afraid well 
send a social worker out there said another counter 
despite the chilly drizzle counters introduced themselves to 
everyone they passed 
im doing it for the money admitted garcia who received 
950 an hour but i live right in this neighborhood and i hope 
it makes a difference besides this isnt a job its an 
adventure 
shortly before 4 am a car pulled up and rolled down a window 
hey isnt it too late to take a census 
several counters replied in unison its never too late for a 
census 
