<TEXT>
illegal immigration along the southwestern 
border has surged in recent months reversing a threeyear downturn 
that began when the federal government told employers they could 
not hire undocumented workers 
according to figures from the immigration and naturalization 
service apprehensions of illegal aliens along the southwest border 
were up in each of the last 10 months compared with the same month 
a year ago 
ins spokesman verne jervis said the rise in apprehensions 
considered to be the best indicator of illegal immigration began 
in may 1989 and continued through february 
according to the ins figures apprehensions of illegal aliens 
were up 299 percent over the last 10 months compared with the 
same period a year ago apprehensions totaled 801937 over the 
period compared with 617317 from may 1988 through february 1989 
some months recorded surges of nearly 60 percent while in other 
months the increases dropped below 20 percent 
the last three months have been among the highest with 
apprehensions rising 573 percent in february from a year earlier 
by 396 percent in january 1990 from the previous january and by 
583 in december 1989 over the same month in 1988 
although the trend in apprehensions continued downward through 
the fiscal year that ended last sept 30 the first six months of 
this fiscal year have seen an increase in apprehensions of 37 
percent over the same period a year ago 
apprehensions had begun dropping sharply in fiscal 1987 a year 
after congress passed and president reagan signed the immigration 
control and reform act of 1986 
the law made employers subject to civil and criminal sanctions 
for hiring undocumented workers 
jervis said the recent rise in illegal immigration may be due to 
the availablity of fradulent documents which undocumented workers 
use to obtain work or simply to the desperation of some 
mexicans seeking work in the united states 
jervis said the bush administrations budget for the fiscal year 
that begins oct 1 seeks an increase in money for the border patrol 
to 2892 million from the current 2626 million 
the administration wants to raise the number of border guards 
from 4852 to 4942 
</TEXT>
