<TEXT>
the state department on wednesday welcomed the 
resumption of food delivery to rebelheld territory in northern 
ethiopia but said only a small fraction of starving people are 
being reached 
eleven trucks carrying 120 tons of us donated food crossed 
tuesday from governmentheld territory to an area controlled by the 
tigrean peoples liberation front said state department deputy 
spokesman richard boucher 
a second convoy is expected to travel thursday 
we welcome the movement of this test convoy made possible by 
informal agreement among the warring parties in ethiopia boucher 
said the government of ethiopia its relief organization 
numerous private voluntary agencies and the concerned rebel groups 
each in their way deserve credit 
boucher said that 4 million to 5 million ethiopians face 
starvation but that only a small fraction of them will be reached 
whatever the success of the new operation 
there is an urgent necessity of opening other relief corridors 
and for the warring parties to give top priority to feeding the 
hungry he said 
boucher called for the reopening of the red sea port of massawa 
to food shipments and said internationally supervised food 
distributions should be made from there into eritrea the countrys 
northernmost province 
according to un estimates more than 1 million people are 
threatened with starvation in eritrea alone 
agreements must be reached for airlifts into affected areas as 
needed whether controlled by the government or by insurgents 
boucher said 
the relief effort is the first since eritrean rebels launched an 
offensive in early february and overran the port of massawa 
</TEXT>
