<TEXT>
some sights and sounds from the nations first homeless census 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
willie smith and sharon johnson two people among the thousands 
of homeless in san francisco were glad to cooperate when us 
census bureau workers came calling with their questions 
were all humans and this count makes us feel like weve all 
got a little respect as human beings the 37yearold smith said 
tuesday night at the piercearrow episcopal community services 
shelter in the citys tenderloin district 
smith homeless in san francisco for two years sat in front of 
a poster of former presidents nixon ford and carter in the crowded 
shelter as he and others answered questions about their age race 
marital status and ethnic origin 
why sure answered johnson resident of another episcopal 
shelter when asked if she wanted to take part in the survey i 
exist dont i im part of the population of this country 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
at baloney joes shelter in portland ore george whitney 
filled out the forms but he was not impressed by the census 
its just the people in their ivory tower drinking their mint 
juleps and counting noses he said nobody can help the 
homeless because nobody understands the problem 
the city of portland agreed to pay 30 homeless people 20 apiece 
to guide census workers to homeless camps 
the census bureau identified 150 sites most of them shelters 
and hotels plus about 70 homeless camps or other street locations 
that were taken from a list compiled by the city 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
occasional light rain fell in sioux falls sd as census 
workers patroled downtown streets after crowds walked and drove 
away following the 2 am closing time for bars the streets were 
deserted except for just a few pedestrians and cars 
census counters jill baldwin and dennis labore stood on a corner 
checking passing pedestrians 
we havent run into any problems its been real quiet 
baldwin said theres not many people out 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
because it was a chilly night in miami about 55 degrees many 
of the homeless gathered in doorways some downtown built small 
fires 
in one stretch of abandoned buildings more than 50 homeless 
people slept on the sidewalk a car filled with enumerators as 
the census counters are called rode slowly past 
in the innercity overtown section the site of three riots 
during the 1980s a threeperson census team encountered little 
hostility among the homeless 
some of them knew all about the census one lady we counted 
said she worked as a census taker 10 years ago said gregory 
williams williams also counted a homeless man who keeps his 
possessions hidden in a tree 
like many enumerators in miami all members of the overtown team 
removed their jewelry and did not carry valuable items 
sure we were a little scared but just dont let them see the 
fear in your eyes said olivia hawkins 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
in lawton okla john wolfenbarger let census workers run 
extension cords into his shady sams pawn shop to run microwave 
ovens that supplied the homeless with fresh hot dogs all night 
wolfenbarger donated the hot dogs 
ive always had a place to lay down but i have feelings for 
those people wolfenbarger said theyre no different from 
anybody else 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
every night for the past 18 years the world ignored richard 
bryant 
tuesday night everyone wanted to know his name age race sex 
and marital status 
while 15000 us census counters fanned out across the united 
states to count the homeless bryant sat in a shelter in 
charleston wva smoking cigarettes and watching television with 
a 39yearold arkansas drifter a jobless north carolina man and a 
dozen other homeless men 
ive learned to live with the fact that im one of the chosen 
outcasts he said in a coarse morningafter rumble 
bryant who has been homeless since 1972 said he is a korean 
war veteran and a master carpenter he smokes marijuana and drinks 
but ascribes his plight to a society that wont accept 
nonconformity 
like others in the shelter he was approached earlier in the 
evening by the census takers he laughs when asked about it 
i truly believe the government is like everyone else they 
have good intentions but no direction its like everything the 
government does it gets so involved and so complicated that very 
little good comes out of it 
he is asked about his future 
is it going to be better i dont know if i make it to 
tomorrow great if i dont make it even better im delivered 
from this 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
shortly after dawn three census workers in san diego county 
calif walked into a canyon where about 100 migrant workers live 
in shacks made of plywood sheet metal and heavy plastic the 
census workers were there to interview the men before most of them 
left in search of daily jobs but some of the migrants said the 
census takers passed them by 
they just walked right past us they didnt ask us anything 
said a migrant worker who declined to give his name there were 
two of them and they met another one on top of the hill and walked 
over it we havent seen them since 
michael j weiler assistant regional census manager said in a 
telephone interview that he would look into the migrant census 
takers actions 
there could have been several things that came up theyre not 
supposed to wake people up he said 
when asked why census takers would walk past people he said 
ill just have to look into that 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
at 230 am two men trudged along the railroad tracks running 
along the vermont shore of lake champlain they tried to keep warm 
in the face of whipping winds and driving snow 
one of them had neither boots nor gloves with a wind of 14 mph 
the wind chill was about 9 degrees 
this is not a night for anybody to be outside said bill 
timbers one of the two 
an observer might have mistaken them for homeless but timbers 
and paul dufresne were in fact census takers on a futile search 
for the homeless 
the pair walked through streets peered into trash dumps 
rummaged through boxes and plastic crates shined their flashlights 
into doorways and alleys and came up empty the homeless 
apparently were staying out of the cold the counters said they 
didnt mind 
the one thing i am glad about is that we didnt count anybody 
out here tonight dufresne said 
</TEXT>
