<TEXT>
after six weeks of testimony the case 
of former exxon valdez captain joseph hazelwood has gone to the 
jury 
the exxon valdez rammed bligh reef in alaskas prince william 
sound on march 24 1989 spilling almost 11 million gallons of 
alaska crude oil and devastating fisheries and wildlife 
hazelwood is charged with criminal mischief reckless 
endangerment operating a vessel while intoxicated and negligent 
discharge of oil in the grounding if convicted he could receive 
7 years in prison and 61000 in fines 
the prosecution contends hazelwood was drunk and reckless while 
in charge of the exxon valdez and risked his ship and crew before 
and after the grounding the defense counters that his judgment was 
not impaired he showed no signs of inebriation and he gave prudent 
commands to protect the safety of ship and crew 
here are some key points raised by the two sides in hazelwoods 
trial 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
prosecution hazelwood was reckless in leaving the bridge in 
control of the third mate during a hazardous transit 
defense it is part of the captains job to delegate 
responsibility another captain testified that he does not consider 
prince william sound hazardous he had left the bridge of his 
vessel in the same area and there is no regulation requiring the 
captain to be on the bridge during the transit 
 
prosecution the third mate left in charge of the bridge had no 
license to pilot the ship within prince william sound hazelwood 
was the only one aboard who had such a license 
defense another captain testified he didnt have a pilots 
license for prince william sound and believed there was no 
requirement for a pilot to be aboard a ship transiting that area 
he cited a letter from the alaska maritime agency advising 
captains in 1986 of a change in pilotage requirements 
 
prosecution chief mate james kunkel testified he warned 
hazelwood that helmsman robert kagan needed practice in 
steering and required special supervision in even the 
simplest tasks 
defense kunkel also said kagan was capable of executing a 
simple 10degree right rudder turn the missed turn that would 
have steered the tanker away from the reef another witness said 
the order was so simple it could have been executed by a 5yearold 
 
prosecution hazelwood told the third mate gregory cousins to 
divert the tanker from normal shipping lanes to avoid ice but 
never gave specific steering directions as a result cousins wound 
up racing between the chart room and the radar screen trying to 
work out the proper maneuver and had no time to keep an eye on 
kagan 
defense hazelwood left clear instruction for the iceavoidance 
maneuver and if the instructions had been followed the valdez 
would have cleared bligh reef when hazelwood asked cousins if he 
felt comfortable with what he had to do cousins replied in the 
affirmative 
 
prosecution hazelwood risked the lives of crew members by not 
ringing a general alarm and letting them sleep through the disaster 
defense kunkel said they discussed abandoning ship but feared 
there would be panic and that putting the crew in oilpolluted 
water in the middle of the night was riskier he said hazelwood 
gave orders to wake the crew by going from cabin to cabin 
 
prosecution hazelwood risked the crew and ship when he 
recklessly tried to extricate the grounded tanker off bligh reef by 
frantically revving the engines and maneuvering the rudder without 
having sufficient information to determine the vessels stability 
hazelwood told the coast guard he was trying to get off the reef 
defense hazelwoods maneuvers after the grounding were 
professional attempts to stabilize the ship he was not trying to 
move or extricate it the point became all but moot when the judge 
ruled the ship was incapable of moving anywhere and could not have 
sunk as prosecution witnesses claimed 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
prosecution hazelwood had five drinks and spent perhaps seven 
hours in a bar drinking before sailing 
defense hazelwood had two or three drinks and spent only three 
hours in the bar 
 
prosecution three witnesses two of them coast coast 
investigators said they smelled alcohol on hazelwoods breath 
crew members saw hazelwood drinking in valdez that day before they 
sailed 
defense crew members testified that hazelwood negotiated a 
precarious gangplank to the ship without a misstep and appeared 
sober as he gave orders defense suggested hazelwood drank a 
lowalcohol brew while on the ship accounting for the alcohol 
smell 
 
prosecution an expert using a method called retrograde 
extrapolation concluded that hazelwoods level of intoxication at 
the time of the shipwreck was 14 percent based on blood and urine 
tests taken 10 hours afterward at the time of the test hazelwood 
had a blood alcohol level of 061 percent the legal limit for 
driving a car in alaska is 10 percent 
defense the retroactive test is only useful for periods of 23 
hours after an incident and if hazelwood drank anything after the 
accident the results of such an extrapolation would be invalid 
their experts called the calculations nonsense 
 
prosecution one could hear that hazelwood was drunk by the rate 
and pitch of his voice on a tape made by the coast guard when the 
ship went aground 
defense a taperecording expert said the tape was a poor copy 
that did not accurately reflect hazelwoods voice the witness also 
said that while slurred speech might be an indication of 
drunkenness changes in the rate of speech or pitch were not 
