a convoy of trucks unloaded at 
least 110 tons of food for famine victims wednesday after safely 
passing through wartorn northern ethiopia 
the 11 trucks arrived tuesday night in kobo in the wollo 
province after leaving the provincial capital of dessie at dawn on 
a 75mile journey over mountainous roads through contested 
territory 
the convoy was the first relief effort since early february 
when a rebel offensive closed a red sea port being used to unload 
supplies 
the state department on wednesday welcomed the resumption of 
food delivery to rebelheld territory but said only a small 
fraction of starving people are being reached 
sponsors of the convoy hope to feed about one million people in 
the provinces of wollo tigre and southern eritrea until next 
december when the harvest is due 
the united nations estimates that more than 4 million people in 
northern ethiopia are in danger of starvation caused by drought and 
war 
we are excited we think the whole trip was a success said 
hamed bahget deputy director of catholic relief services in 
ethiopias capital addis ababa there was no hitch 
the trip was completed without a formal ceasefire between the 
government and the tigre peoples liberation front which has 
controlled much of wollo province since late last year 
both sides have promised safety for the convoys operated by a 
consortium of ethiopian church groups with money and food donations 
mostly from the united states and western europe 
privately relief workers say the promise of safe passage could 
be revoked at any time because of either error or suspicion that 
the convoys are being used to smuggle war material 
the tigreans have been fighting since 1975 to oust president 
mengistu haile mariam and establish a government similar to 
albania the last orthodox communist government in eastern europe 
the trucks are scheduled to return to dressie on thursday when 
a second convoy will leave for another town in wollo or tigre 
the church groups hope to extend their distribution network from 
wollo and tigre into southern eritrea 
eritrea the countrys northernmost province is largely 
controlled by another larger rebel group the secessionist eritrea 
peoples liberation front the united nations says more than one 
million people are threatened with starvation in eritrea alone 
the ethiopian government and tigre rebels on wednesday began a 
third round of preliminary talks aimed at ending their 15yearold 
conflict 
the italian foreign ministry an observer at the meetings said 
the talks centered on the composition of the delegations the 
agenda for fullfledged negotiations and ways to end the fighting 
the government delegation was headed by deputy prime minister 
ashagre ygletu meles zenawi president of the tigre peoples 
liberation front led the rebel delegation 
earlier talks were held in rome on nov 411 and dec 1219 the 
current session is aimed at achieving fullscale peace negotiations 
to be presided over by italy and kenya 
