<TEXT>
with californias drought entering its fourth 
year the largest water agency supplying southern california wants 
mandatory conservation rules banning driveway washing daytime lawn 
watering and car washing 
even if we had rain of biblical proportions we couldnt get 
back to normal this year bob gomperz spokesman for the 
metropolitan water district said wednesday 
the district imports water into the desertlike region by 
aqueducts from the colorado river and northern california and 
sells it wholesale to 27 smaller water districts 
the agency supplies more than 500 billion gallons yearly to the 
13 million residents of a sixcounty area containing 300 
communities from ventura county to the mexico border the area 
includes los angeles and san diego 
californias rainy season is just about over mountain snowpack 
levels are running at less than 63 percent of normal and river 
runoff is 35 percent of normal the states cooperative snow survey 
reports 
most of the season is over already the thing is cast now 
its grim said the surveys jack pardee 
runoff in the sierra nevada range fell to 63 percent of normal 
in 1987 60 percent of normal in 1988 and 64 percent last year so 
far in 1990 the runoff has been 63 percent 
the region also has lost some of the water it took from the 
colorado river water as arizona has begun using more of its 
entitlement from the heavily allocated river the projected 
reduction was about 300000 acrefeet or approximately the amount 
used by 700000 households annually 
there is a possibility that southern california could 
experience shortages even with normal precipitation for the 
rest of the year said district general manager carl boronkay 
if the shortage is as serious as i think it is then its 
time we all got serious and began mandatory programs to cut 
usage boronkay said 
if communities begin watersaving measures immediately most of 
the region could avoid being forced to take such drastic steps as 
have been taken in santa barbara northwest of los angeles where 
watering lawns is now illegal 
statewide several communities have resorted to rationing 
monterey county on the central coast is holding consumers to 80 
percent of their past consumption rate santa clara county 
southeast of san francisco has rationed water at 75 percent of 
normal the central valley water project has cut the flow of water 
up to 50 percent 
and el dorado county including part of the sierra nevada east 
of sacramento has banned new water connections 
the metropolitan water district estimates that supplies could 
fall short of demand by up to 12 percent in the coming year the 
agency also warned that mandatory water rationing may be necessary 
if there isnt some improvement next year 
conservation measures it wants to impose include banning hosing 
down driveways watering lawns during daylight washing cars and 
serving water in restaurants without a customer request 
but the los angeles department of water and power which gets 
about half its water from the district doesnt feel those measures 
will be enough to alleviate shortages it also gets water from 
wells 
