<TEXT>
the bush administration has endorsed an 
international agreement to control the export and disposal of 
hazardous waste the white house said wednesday 
the united nations basel convention on controlling crossborder 
shipments of hazardous waste prohibits such shipments unless the 
exporting country does not have the technical capability or 
adequate facilities to dispose of it it also allows export for 
recycling 
the convention covers household and infectious wastes and 
municipal incinerator residue as well as hazardous waste 
an anaylst for natural resources defense council an 
environmental group called the convention a modest first step 
toward ending dumping of waste from industrial countries on third 
world countries 
we believe that trade must end anything short of a treaty to 
end all trade is unacceptable said jane bloom senior attorney 
for nrdc 
the united states has a separate agreement covering exports of 
us hazardous waste to mexico and canada 
president bush said a year ago that hazardous waste would be 
exported from the united states only to countries that agreed to 
handle it in an environmentally safe manner 
bush will send congress legislation to implement both that 
policy and the basel accord 
the 1989 basel convention signed by 46 countries was the first 
of its kind calling for keeping crossborder hazardous waste 
shipments to a minimum 
the senate must ratify the treaty which bars waste exports to 
antarctica for bushs endorsement to become policy the policy 
intends to cut down on using african and other third world 
countries as dumping grounds 
environmental groups however have complained that it legalizes 
the international waste trade and that it was weakened to please 
industrialized countries 
the basel agreement says waste exports are to be barred if there 
is reason to believe the importing country will not manage them in 
an environmentally sound manner countries through which waste 
shipments pass must be notified and give written consent 
the agreement says that a country can export such waste if it 
does not have the technical capacity facilities or sites to 
dispose of it in an environmentally sound and efficient manner the 
white house said 
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

