<TEXT>
an estimated 2000 to 5000 epilepsy patients 
a year are candidates for brain surgery using sophisticated new 
imaging techniques to provide surgeons a road map for the removal 
of abnormal brain cells 
in a report released at a news conference wednesday a national 
institutes of health committee of experts said that 150000 
americans annually have a first epiletic attack and many go on to 
develop a persistent pattern of seizures some with up to 20 
attacks a week 
anticonvulsant drugs will control seizures in about 70 percent 
of epilepsy patients but 10 percent to 20 percent are not helped 
by such medication 
many of these patients and their families have to deal with a 
chronic disorder that impairs the quality of life for all 
concerned the committee reported 
for those with intractable epilepsy the panel said surgery 
offers the only hope of relief 
the nih convened the panel of 13 experts to study epilepsy 
surgery and to make treatment recommendations for use by the 
nations medical community 
about 500 operations to control epilepsy are performed annually 
in the united states and the panel said the procedure is 
considered successful in 50 percent to 70 percent of the patients 
dr lewis p rowland director of neurological service at 
columbia presbyterian medical center in new york said epilepsy 
surgery consists of locating and removing the group of brain cells 
responsible for the seizures 
rowland chairman of the panel said surgeons remove a portion 
of the skull cut into the brain to remove the problem cells and 
restore the skull bone 
locating the problem cells he said now can be done using 
imaging techniques that use sophisticated computerdriven xrays 
or magnetic resonance imaging 
we can do a a very precise operation now said dr edward r 
laws professor of neurosurgery at george washington university 
medical center in washington we can map the brain and know 
exactly the location of centers that cause the seizures 
death or injury to healthy parts of the brain are very uncommon 
from such operations laws said 
its practical now to do this type of surgery he said 
laws said that most common epileptic surgery targets the 
temporal lobe the portion of the brain at the temple about 70 
percent of those operations are successful with the patients 
recovering either with no seizures or with seizures that can be 
controlled by drugs 
a more complicated procedure is in the frontal lobe of the 
brain that portion beneath the forehead 
results here fall to about 50 percent laws said 
such operations have been performed on children under the age of 
2 but rowland said the average age of epileptic surgery patients 
is 27 
cost of the operations average about 40000 but can run as 
high as 100000 much of the expense comes from the use of 
sophisticated equipment to map the brain and to plan the surgery 
the surgery is covered by some insurance companies and partially 
covered by medicaid in some states 
in their committee report the experts recommended that 
epileptic surgery be limited to those hospitals with the equipment 
and staff to attempt such a complicated procedure 
the committee also said a diagnosis of the epilepsy should be 
confirmed through tests that all patients receive a careful trial 
of drug therapy and that a full range of tests be conducted to 
precisely locate the flawed brain cells that cause the seizures 
</TEXT>
