<TEXT>
ethnic hatreds that have flared in the 
romanian city of tirgu mures are as old as the squabble over 
transylvania now part of romania but administered for centuries by 
neighboring hungary 
at least six people were reported dead wednesday in the 
transylvanian city about 250 miles north of bucharest and the same 
distance east of budapest about 300 were wounded in pitched street 
battles between ethnic hungarians and romanians some armed with 
wooden staves scythes and pitchforks 
the violence followed weeks of increasing tension over demands 
of transylvanias 22 millionstrong hungarian minority about 10 
percent of romanias population 
among the rights sought by ethnic hungarians were 
reestablishment of separate hungarianlanguage schools and 
universities initially supported by the postworld war ii romanian 
leadership but abolished under toppled dictator nicolae ceausescu 
and proportional government representation on the local and 
national level 
weeks of peaceful demonstrations in transylvania by both ethnic 
groups turned into open conflict on the weekend over an apparently 
minor incident a hungarianlanguage sign in a tirgu mures store 
window identifying it as a pharmacy 
a group of romanians demolished the pharmacy and attacked the 
headquarters of the democratic federation of hungarians the main 
special interest group of the minority street battles followed 
and the army moved in to try to restore order 
the tirgu mures clashes represented the first documented case of 
open ethnic violence in transylvania in more than 40 years and 
displayed the depth of emotions kept in check under the iron hand 
of ceausescu and his predecessor gheorghe gheorghiudej 
while their communist systems perpetuated and later encouraged 
the hatreds as a way of diffusing opposition to authoritarian rule 
both leaders would have moved quickly to crush any open ethnic 
conflict that could have developed into a threat to their authority 
nationalist rivalries seemingly faded in december as the two 
ethnic groups joined in anticeausescu demonstrations in timisoara 
another transylvanian city starting what quickly turned into the 
revolution but bickering along ethnic lines quickly resurfaced 
romanians and hungarians have been in transylvania more than 
1000 years and hungarian kings ruled the territory in the middle 
ages the modern history of the conflict dates to the 1830s with 
awakening nationalist sentiment across europe 
in 1848 the hungarians rose against austrian rule they 
demanded recognition of their own national aspirations without 
being willing to extend similar recognition to likeminded desires 
of national minorities in the region 
hungarian revolutionaries sought the annexation of transylvania 
then administered by austria the hungarians lost their 
independence battle but subsequently gained control of transylvania 
as junior partners in the austrohungarian monarchy 
one incident indirectly leading to the tirgu mures violence was 
romanian displeasure with open ethnic hungarian celebrations of 
march 15 the anniversary of the outbreak of the antiaustrian 
revolution such dates could not be observed during the communist 
era 
after dissolution of the austrohungarian empire in 1918 the 
victorious allies of world war i ceded transylvania to romania 
under the treaty of trianon recurring hungarian repression of 
transylvanian romanians was replaced by officially condoned 
romanian persecution of the regions hungarians 
hungary reclaimed part of transylvania as a reward for 
temporarily siding with nazi germany during world war ii only to 
lose it again at the end of the war with the defeat of the axis 
</TEXT>
