<TEXT>
the federal communications commission on 
wednesday further narrowed the field of contestants locked in a 
highstakes battle to win the right to market a highdefinition 
television transmission system 
chairman alfred sikes said the commission which plans to 
announce the winner of the hdtv sweepstakes in early 1993 voted to 
consider only hdtv systems that will not require use of an extra 
augmentation channel of scarce tv space in order to provide the 
crystalclear pictures and compact discquality sound that the new 
system promises 
at the moment no augmentation system is expected but some 
could emerge or be revived 
only socalled simulcast systems will be considered for testing 
at the advanced television test center this fall sikes said at a 
meeting of the fccs advisory committee on advanced television 
service 
japanese and european manufacturers are far ahead of the united 
states in developing the next generation of television which 
promises many military educational and medical uses besides giving 
viewers motion picturequality views of roseanne 
the test center is to recommend the winning system to the fcc in 
the fall of 1992 
in a simulcast system a tv station would broadcast its regular 
tv signal on one channel and the same program on another channel in 
highdefinition for instance the regular signal on channel 9 and 
the highdefinition signal on channel 12 
commission engineers believe there are enough unused channels so 
that most broadcasters would be able to adopt simulcast hdtv 
systems 
augmentation systems on the other hand also use two channels 
but use the second channel to provide a signal that when combined 
in the tv set with the regular signal on the first channel yields 
the highdefinition picture 
of the nine companies or groups planning to offer hdtv systems 
for testing only one proposed an augmentationtype approach and 
the proposal has been scrapped said peter fannon executive 
director of the test center 
that proposal was the actv2 system from the david sarnoff 
research center thomson consumer electronics and nbc the proposal 
was killed earlier this year when sarnoff joined forces with 
another hdtv proponent philips consumer electronics co 
the new york institute of technology also has said it wanted to 
submit an augmentation system but it had not come up with the 
money to do so fannon said 
in making this determination we are aware of the fact that 
augmentationtype systems could also provide a quality 
highdefinition television service sikes said however we 
find that the substantial spectrum availability and utilization 
problems that selection of an augmentationtype system would entail 
indicates that further testing of such systems is not warranted 
in our judgment the interests of the public will be better 
served by selecting a simulcast system 
sikes also said the commission was committed to first adopting a 
transmission standard for full highdefinition television and then 
if necessary considering socalled enhanceddefinition that would 
todays signals without achieving true hdtv 
the commission has said previously that any hdtv system it 
selects for us transmissions must be compatible with the existing 
tv system to avoid making every tv set in the nation obsolete 
fannon said wednesdays decision leaves eight entrants in the 
testing program five have already been certified sarnoffphilips 
an analog simulcast system from philips zenith electronics corp 
and the narrow muse and muse6 systems from the japan broadcasting 
corp 
three others need to complete the certification process by june 
or lose their test slots faroudja laboratories of sunnyvale 
calif production services inc of tucson ariz and the 
massachusetts institute of technology 
the faroudja actv and muse 6 systems provide an 
enhanceddefinition signal that removes some of the ghosts and 
squiggles that mar todays systems 
entrants will be required to put up 175000 toward actual test 
costs which fannon said would reach 12 million and 15 million 
the test program is being financed by the television and 
electronics industries 
