flooding rivers receded wednesday in most of alabama and some 
evacuees returned to homes and businesses while florida officials 
worked to evacuate people remaining in the path of rising water 
president bush declared parts of southeast alabama a major 
disaster area wednesday night making individuals and local 
governments in coffee county including hardhit elba eligible for 
federal grants and lowinterest loans the white house said other 
areas may be designated for assistance later 
some central georgia cities along swollen waterways began to 
recover from flooding wednesday but cities in the southern part of 
the state were told to prepare for their share of problems 
flooding in the florida panhandle had already forced evacuation 
of almost 2200 people and state officials predicted more than 
1700 of them might have to remain out of their homes for several 
days 
many of the 2000 evacuees from hardhit elba ala returned 
while emergency crews tried to restore clean water power and 
telephone lines to the mudcaked city 
for some the return five days after up to 16 inches of rain 
fell was devastating 
theres three generations of antiques and family heirlooms in 
there becky hayes said as she stood outside a mudcovered 
warehouse her family owns near elbas town square now its all 
upside down like scrambled eggs 
gene malfer a spokesman for the american red cross said the 
organization estimated that 239 homes in elba were destroyed 286 
suffered major damage and about 70 had minor damage 
a building sat in the middle of an intersection where it was 
left by high water from the pea river that poured over a broken 
levee early saturday vehicles at a usedcar dealership were piled 
on top of each other 
allen morse of the army corps of engineers who is overseeing 
the levee rebuilding process said the first priority is 
temporarily filling four breaks in the elba levee because of the 
likelihood of more rain he said permanent repairs could take 30 
days in ideal conditions 
the flooding was blamed for 11 deaths in alabama 
traffic was backed up as evacuees headed into elba slowed by 
national guard soldiers who set up identification checkpoints to 
allow in only those with homes and businesses in the floodravaged 
area 
however numerous sightseers apparently got by the barriers 
forcing officials to evacuate the town for a few hours to clear the 
streets a gas leak at a high school also prompted a brief 
evacuation from the school 
most homes outside elbas levee had power but fresh water was 
being trucked in as health officials advised against drinking city 
water 
the local high school and middle school which were completely 
covered by water over the weekend still had several inches of 
water inside wednesday but around the coffee county courthouse 
square nothing was left but gooey red mud 
water also had covered the first floor of the courthouse where 
probate childsupport criminal and civil records are stored 
we dont know to what extent the records are salvagable 
said allen tapley of the state administrative office of the courts 
tapley said records of about onethird of alabamas court 
systems have been placed on microfilm mostly in urban areas elba 
though still keeps most of its records on paper 
the worst of floridas flooding came along the choctawhatchee 
river as water from last weeks rain flowed downhill from alabama 
and georgia 
hardest hit was the farming community of caryville where 
emergency official rod westall said the choctawhatchee was 
beginning to recede but not by very much caryville will not be 
out from under water until probably sunday 
the choctawhatchee crested near caryville at 92 feet above 
flood stage late tuesday but was still about 89 feet above flood 
stage wednesday said westall 
caryville usually has a population of about 600 this week 
chickens roosted in trees and a swarm of fire ants floated through 
the middle of town 
the choctawhatchee river south of caryville is still rising 
said westall theres not much down there but there are some 
people fish camps weekend cabins theres not a lot of 
people 
some residents refused to leave their homes including willard 
bailey 56 a semiretired mechanic from caryville he was living 
in a houseboat that was tied to his house sitting in 5 feet of 
water 
i built it a couple of years ago never put it in the 
river bailey said as he maneuvered another smaller boat 
through city streets the river came to it the river floated it 
off the trailer 
in macon ga the ocmulgee river began to recede and officials 
said preliminary tests showed no contamination of the citycounty 
water supply from flooding however residents were asked to boil 
water or drink bottled water as a precaution 
