<TEXT>
six months after hurricane hugo south 
carolinas timber industry faces major fire threats and a long 
recovery but tourism and other state industries are rebounding 
gov carroll campbell said wednesday 
south carolinians and south carolina deserve the comeback of 
the year award campbell said in releasing a report on relief 
efforts since the storm 
though much of the state has returned to normal 10000 people 
still are displaced and economic impacts on most state industries 
will be felt for at least another year campbell said 
the report was released in the same conference room where 
campbell and other top aides coordinated emergency efforts as the 
storm roared ashore near charleston on sept 21 with 135mph winds 
and storm surges reaching 15 feet the storm left 29 dead and 59 
billion in damage in south carolina 
this thing was a monster campbell said 
since the storm about 200 million in state and federal funds 
have been set aside for local and state governments to rebuild 
public structures and pay such costs as overtime for cleanup 
workers 
about another 200 million has been or will be distributed 
through private and public agencies in affected areas 
an eightmember economic recovery commission appointed by the 
governor is scheduled to present recommendations next week 
campbell said tourism has come back strongly with inquiries 
running at a record pace and traffic at state travel information 
centers up 12 percent from a year ago 
but the timber industry will take much longer to recuperate 
campbell said though he offered no timetable 
according to the report 23 weeks of harvesting have brought 
timber salvage efforts to 41 percent of their goal of 625 million 
