<TEXT>
miscommunications between technicians and computer 
engineers were to blame for the failure of a martin marietta corp 
rocket to deploy a 150 million communications satellite company 
officials said 
the commercial titan was wired to carry two satellites when only 
one was aboard company officials said monday 
the 5ton intelsat satellite was left stranded in space last 
wednesday when it failed to separate from the rockets upper stage 
a clamshelllike device that can house up to two satellites the 
satellite remains in an orbit closer to earth than is useful with 
little chance for recovery 
the mistake may cost as much as 500 million including lost 
revenue from transmitting telephone calls and television signals 
space analysts say 
the technicians in charge of the boosters electric system and 
the computer software engineers were working in the same building 
martin marietta officials said 
no one was goofing off or being secretive said company 
spokesman steve frank it was language that each group thought 
meant the same thing 
martin marietta officials at cape canaveral fla found the 
same wiring problem in an identical commercial titan rocket 
scheduled to be launched in june carrying another intelsat 
satellite 
a board of inquiry has been formed to investigate the incident 
and recommend improvements frank said 
company investigators found that martin marietta electricians 
apparently wired the rocket in a configuration allowing it to 
release two satellites the wires in turn were connected to a 
computer that was supposed to trigger the separation of the 
satellite from the rocket 
when ground crews ordered the computer to send its signal the 
faulty design prevented it from traveling past the satellite to the 
separation device 
it was a case where the computer people said they would launch 
the first payload and the wiring people thought that meant the 
bottom payload compartment frank said there was just nothing 
at the separation device to receive the signal 
the denver post today quoted anonymous sources close to the 
investigation as saying the company is likely to adopt prelaunch 
checks including a mock satellite separation on the ground using 
the firing commands employed in space 
