<TEXT>
president chadli bendjedid is pushing algeria 
toward democracy but at a cautious pace 
islamic fundamentalists oppose some of his programs they have 
not been specific about their own vision of algeria however and 
bendjedids position seems secure as he modifies institutions to 
allow more representative government 
bendjedid 61 has made few speeches during 11 years in power 
and rarely appears in public he was a regional military commander 
and got substantial help from the army in attaining the presidency 
in 1979 after the death of houari boumedienne who had left no 
clear successor 
algeria has taken a pronounced turn toward democracy since the 
army has withdrawn from the political councils of the ruling 
national liberation front and professes neutrality 
a popular uprising in 1988 ended the fronts undisputed rule 
over all areas of society and 20 political parties now are 
registered the front holds all the parliament seats but more than 
70 percent of voters approved a constitutional amendment last year 
that in theory makes algeria a multiparty democracy 
multiparty local elections are scheduled for june 12 and 
parliamentary elections are required within two years but the 
country has a long way to go in turning democratic concepts into 
reality 
hundreds of thousands of officials bureaucrats and workers in 
nationalized companies are used to the job security free insurance 
and free health services acquired in a generation of oneparty 
rule the press is allowed to dissent but tends to await official 
guidance on controversial issues 
the results of the changes have become very difficult to 
evaluate in an exhaustive and precise manner but the process is 
beneficial ahcenedjaballah belkacem head of the official news 
agency aps wrote in the government daily el moudjahid 
what had been a a military dictatorship gives new parties 1 
million each to help them get started he wrote the judiciary is 
free of government control citizens feel they can oppose 
government actions and demagogic oratory is less prevalent than 
before belkacem said 
in a cautionary note he added that other aspects of the new 
freedoms such as wildcat strikes and a growing unemployment 
problem are negatives for which we will have to pay a heavy 
price now and for a certain time to come 
abasso madani of the islamic salvation front the largest 
opposition party said algerias main problem is a leadership 
crisis 
in his first televised political statement the opposition 
leader said bendjedid had not given a clear picture of his plans 
for algeria 
madani said little of what his fundamentalists would do a few 
vague words about cutting government expenses including military 
spending and rejecting socialism communism and liberalism 
left listeners uncertain of his political program 
he also was not specific on the rights of women 
any woman who accepts that she is a moslem must accept all the 
consequences that result from this choice madani declared 
causing many women to wonder what he had in mind for them 
fundamentalist leaders have a growing voice in national 
politics but most of their followers are poorly educated 
unemployed men the middle classes and the vast majority of 
algerian women oppose rule by islamic law 
algerians generally are accustomed to supporting or at least 
not challenging whoever holds power that means bendjedid probably 
will continue as president and algeria will develop a form of 
democracy possibly through slow and undramatic steps 
</TEXT>
