<TEXT>
it is an ideal of sorts a seemingly perfect 
target a goal to shoot for but some people think it might have 
terrible consequences such as throwing people out of work and 
undermining the economy 
it is zero inflation and its a temptation 
were the goal to be achieved without real problems it would be a 
crowning achievement for the chairman of the federal reserve and 
his aides it would be their place in history their washington 
monument 
but can it be achieved or is it like an exquisite museum piece 
encased in glass there to be contemplated but never possessed 
nobody really knows 
note the united states has achieved very low inflation such as 
levels of less than 2 percent in the 1960s it has suffered many 
zerominus levels as in the great depression when the economy 
shrank rather than grew 
in fact it actually achieved zero inflation during peacetime 
right on the nose in relatively recent memory in 1936 although it 
is generally agreed that the degree of economic destruction was 
ruinous 
but nobody seems to remember any concerted attempt to reduce 
inflation to zero without slowing the economy to the point where 
recession became the more serious problem 
the controversy is alive again because the notion is making the 
rounds in washington the idea being that only when inflation is 
destroyed will the country be able to safely embark on strong 
growth again 
some powerful people support the idea alan greenspan federal 
reserve chairman hasnt ruled it out martin feldstein former 
chairman of the council of economic advisers thinks it could be 
achieved in five years 
others are emphatically against the attempt such as benjamin 
friedman harvard economics professor he testified in washington 
that a substantial reduction in inflation will involve some 
heavyweight tradeoffs 
the most serious of the tradeoffs is a reduced level of 
economic activity punctuated by lower production lower sales 
higher unemployment reduced revenues for all branches of 
government restraints on social programs 
the list could be endless 
a study by the congressional research service suggests that zero 
inflation within five years achieved by means of restrictive 
monetary policies would bring on a serious recession 
among other consequences it listed these 
negative gross national product for each year of the 1990 to 
1993 period an unemployment rise to 12 percent for 1993 an 
interest rate of 17 percent in 1993 for 90day treasury bills and 
a quadrupling of the budget deficit 
nobody can prove such a scenario but the fearsome possibilities 
are enough to suggest to some people that the effort isnt worth 
taking for them it is probing the unknown the economic 
equivalent of genetic engineering 
john wright bridgeport conn businessman investment adviser 
and economist worries about the pursuit but contends zero 
inflation shouldnt be seen as either necessarily undesirable or 
unachievable per se 
common sense tells us says wright a frequent critic of 
monetary restraints and high interest rates that inflation is 
caused only by an excess of demand over the supply of goods and 
services 
as he sees it restraints on money supply which makes up most 
of the federal reserve antiinflation program is simply a means of 
limiting excessive demand but he observes policies can affect 
both demand and supply 
it would be safer he suggests for the antiinflation program 
to control demand by providing incentives for savings and 
encourage efficient production supply by lowering the cost of 
capital investment 
</TEXT>
