<TEXT>
in september 1974 when busloads of black 
children pulled up for the first time at south boston high school 
the ensuing rockthrowing and racial curses reminded the nation of 
two truths it might have preferred to forget 
the civil rights battles waged in the 1950s and 1960s were far 
from over in the 1970s and the social evils that touched off those 
battles were by no means confined to the south 
the boston school desegregation battle is the subject of the 
commendable common ground a twopart fourhour cbs miniseries 
airing sunday and tuesday 
the programs subject matter though 15 years old still is 
relevant the issues of race and class remain at the core of 
american urban life perhaps nowhere more so than in boston itself 
where last years stuart murder case demonstrated how racial 
divisions in that city persist 
the miniseries four years in the making is based on the 
pulitzer prizewinning book of the same name by j anthony lukas 
it looks at the boston busing battles through the eyes of three 
real boston families deeply affected by it an irishcatholic 
family a black family and a young white liberal married couple 
who move to a racially mixed neighborhood 
jane curtin of kate amp allie and saturday night live 
fame gives an insightful performance as the deeply religious 
irishcatholic alice mcgoff mother of seven and a resident of the 
ultraclannish charlestown neighborhood 
she captures nicely the complexity of a lowermiddleclass white 
woman who does not believe herself a racist but cannot understand 
why as she puts it blacks feel theyre the only ones who have 
it tough 
as her children get swept into the daily racial conflicts that 
eventually spread to charlestown high school mcgoff finds herself 
taking a leading role in the white resistance movement unlike her 
more openly racist neighbors she favors nonviolence and leads 
demonstrators in ironic chants of the lords prayer while battling 
police 
in the end after two years of exhausting demonstrations and 
strife mcgoff learns a lesson in tolerance from her daughter 
lisa who delivers a climactic valedictory speech at charlestown 
high about racial harmony 
cch pounder plays rachel twymon a tough longsuffering 
mother of six in the predominantly black roxbury neighborhood 
she is devoted to the idea of integrating bostons schools but 
the growing militancy and violence goes against her grain twymon 
is portrayed as a hard taskmaster to her children so much so that 
one of her daughters runs away 
richard thomas looks appropriately liberal as colin diver right 
down to the hornedrim glasses as a star law student at harvard 
looking for a way to channel his idealism diver takes a job with 
the thenyoung and charismatic boston mayor kevin white but 
eventually becomes disenchanted with the political machinations 
diver his wife and two children satisfy their thirst for real 
city life by moving to a racially mixed gentrifying neighborhood in 
bostons south end but the realities of that lifestyle the 
crime prostitution and racial animosity eventually send them 
retreating to the suburbs 
common ground is a nicely subtle miniseries that may not 
settle for viewers the pros and cons of the boston busing conflict 
but does reveal much about three families searching desperately for 
decent solutions in angry times the producers lack the time 
however to show as the book does so well who these three 
families are where they and their ancestors came from and most 
importantly the history and background of the boston school 
conflict 
key elements also are lost in some of the portrayals 
in the case of rachel twymon especially the miniseries 
apparently for lack of time draws her as an almost heartless 
disciplinarian of her children without making clear as the book 
does what a hard life she had in fact she was desperately ill 
with the crippling disease lupus which eventually claimed her life 
nonetheless common ground is a praiseworthy miniseries a 
reminder that recent racial incidents in new yorks howard beach 
and elsewhere in urban america show that the civil rights battle 
continues and that there are no easy answers 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
since 1981 
