<TEXT>
when nicolae ceausescu ruled romania 
his secret police watched and listened to everyone opened mail 
inspected packages and made appropriate notations in the dossier of 
each citizen 
at the customs post office on giulesti street in central 
bucharest on the third floor was an assembly line where letters 
and packages mailed by or to people on a list of suspected or 
potential enemies of the state were xrayed analyzed by metal 
detectors or steamed open 
anything incriminating was noted then letters were resealed and 
delivered 
those whose mail was inspected knew nothing of it but they 
might have suspected when police took them in for questioning or 
they heard the thousands of rumors about the securitate secret 
police 
journalists were taken through the mailmonitoring facility this 
month the tour appeared to be part of the provisional governments 
effort to convince foreigners and its own 23 million citizens that 
the securitate has been abolished since the communist dictator was 
deposed and executed in december 
a week before the tour state television showed a uniformed 
officer displaying wrecked telephonetapping equipment 
video cameras were placed in hotels and public buildings and 
near the homes of suspects the securitate was said to have 
hundreds of thousands of informers 
so great was the fear of informers last summer a few months 
before ceausescus downfall that bucharest residents avoided even 
looking at western reporters and few would address them even 
casually 
dispelling such fear would be difficult for any government in 
power only three months 
romanias provisional administration which includes several 
former communists has made the job harder by keeping information 
about the securitate secret such as how many of its officers were 
captured after the ceausescu regime fell 
that secrecy and the fact that many people suspected of being 
informers still have their civilian jobs in factories and offices 
feed popular suspicion that the television broadcast post office 
tour and similar revelations are mostly for show 
in the broadcast the skeptical television reporter asked the 
uniformed officer how long it would take experts to reassemble the 
tangled masses of snapped wires at the dorobanti telephone 
exchange about three days the officer conceded 
maj gen nicolae cerbu deputy commander of the army signal 
corps told reporters at the mail surveillance center that up to 
6000 letters and parcels passed through the office each week 
the attitude toward the regime was a priority in this 
checking and they also did it just out of curiosity cerbu said 
about 1 million letters and packages are mailed in romania each 
day cerbu said 120 people were employed in the tampering operation 
at the customs post office 
packages were xrayed and put through metal detectors to find 
weapons or explosives letters were steamed open by machine and 
read then reglued and sealed 
even casual remarks unflattering to ceausescu or his regime 
could be grounds for persecution 
a 22yearold student still reluctant to tell a western 
reporter her name said the police summoned her two years ago 
