<TEXT>
how could anyone write an autobiography at 
the age of 15 its possible when you consider the young life of 
drew barrymore 
at the age of 6 she was starring in steven spielbergs et 
the extraterrestrial the most successful film of all time she 
was a drinker at 9 marijuana smoker at 10 cocaine user at 12 
recovering addict at 14 
little girl lost pocket books 1795 is the apt title of 
the teenagers memoir written with todd gold the book describes 
in harrowing detail her descent into a juvenile abyss of deception 
excess and degradation the road back has been rocky 
after a wild drunken spree drew underwent 87 days of 
rehabilitation in a hospital released she embarked on another 
bender flying from new york to los angeles on a credit card stolen 
from her mother the second treatment she hopes will be her last 
it was never the work that was the problem with drew it was 
the time inbetween remarks her mother ildiko barrymore that 
is the problem for many actors how to fill that time between the 
jobs the jobs give you a sense of selfworth and accomplishment 
the barrymores have a long history of alcoholism and addiction 
drews grandfather john barrymore and aunt diana were destroyed 
by drink as were members of earlier generations drews father 
john jr has had a long history of addiction he is a menacing 
figure in little girl lost a wildbearded wreck who turned up 
only to abuse his daughter and former wife and ask for money 
i was not aware of the extent that genetic predisposition 
has says ildiko barrymore once you become aware of that you 
deal with it on a level of more intelligence in terms of what needs 
to be done 
drew now 15 and her mother live on a quiet street in the san 
fernando valley one day after school drew sat down for an 
interview always an attractive girl she has turned into a 
teenage beauty and she talks thoughtfully about the tumultuous 
events of her young life 
q how can you write a life story at your age 
a people were saying you should tell your story you should 
tell your story i was really too scared to i got a few 
different offers to write a book and i chose one it was really 
scary to lay your life on the line you dont know what the 
feedback is going to be will it be positive or negative i took 
the risk 
q did you realize you would have to live through the bad 
periods again 
a it was scary in the fact that you would have to bring up 
these issues you had already dealt with or are scared to deal with 
again but i just focused on positive energy and went with the flow 
q how do you answer those who might say youre writing the book 
for exploitation or publicity 
a i certainly wasnt looking for publicity because id gotten 
enough before i wrote the book i know exactly why i wrote it 
theres a lot of parents with kids who may not be addicts or 
alcoholics but who can relate to what ive gone through they could 
know that theyre not alone that was real comforting to me to 
know that im not alone in this situation that im going through 
q was one of your problems that you have spent most of your 
life in an adult world 
a i dont think it really helped but it was more me in 
wanting to fit in so badly and to be at their level so badly i 
thought that was what i was supposed to do 
q did steven spielberg have an important influence on you 
a he is probably the most important male ever in my life he 
means everything to me hes given me a lot of experience a lot of 
good advice the nurturing i never got from my dad he filled a lot 
of empty spaces just by being there 
q what was your relationship to your father 
a the little bit of relationship that there was was very 
abusive and just chaotic even though it was like that i just 
wasnt going to accept that he wasnt going to come back i had 
this fantasy in my mind that i was going to have father knows 
best walk through the door i wanted that so bad and i wasnt 
going to face reality that it wasnt going to happen 
q even though your mother was loving and supportive you had 
resentments with her why 
a when i was little she had to work all the time i felt like 
she was abandoning me but she really wasnt she was just working 
and making money for us later on i just wasnt there at all i 
would turn the table around and say that she wasnt there for me 
every time she would be with me id walk out the door there was a 
lot of friction there 
q what was your lowest point 
a probably when i went back into rehab the last time i had hit 
many emotional bottoms but there was always 1 percent of me out of 
100 that thought i would make it out this time i honestly did not 
think i would make it out through sheer love of people i cared 
about and my own wanting it for nobody but myself i worked through 
it but it was really scary 
q what is your life like today 
a its very calm and mellow there are times when its in the 
fast lane and there are times when its in the slooow lane im 
usually somewhere inbetween which is where i always wanted to be 
im living life one day at a time i go to meetings i go to 
movies i act stupid im not afraid to be my age anymore then 
there are times when i act like 20 
i was always so scared to ever ever ever act my age scared 
what people would think now i really dont care because i have 
fun 
q what do you do when people offer you a drink 
a as soon as i got sober it has been eight months now i 
havent had many days of temptation so if anyone doesnt know im 
sober and they offer me a drink i automatically say no 
its hard i have to make sure i dont go in slippery places 
with slippery people i have to make sure that i dont say anything 
rude to my mom by accident because thats what i used to do at 
first it was like walking on egg shells but day by day it gets 
better and better 
</TEXT>
