<TEXT>
its kind of like falling in love 
your favorite treasure is a meissen figurine that once belonged 
to your aunt one day you spot another maybe in a little shop and 
you have to have it 
by the time you find a third youre head over heels and willing 
to spend a weeks salary in short youre a collector 
bob rau collects art glass while dana garrett has a soft spot 
for scotty dogs as creators and cohosts of the collectors 
series on pbs rau and garrett have seen passions ranging from 
classic cars to fine crystal from priceless antiques to 
twoperpenny baseball cards and vintage bowling shirts 
says rau enthusiasm makes great television 
now in its fourth season the collectors is distributed to 
262 stations nationwide statistically 82 percent of the homes 
using television it is by far the most successful locally produced 
program in the history of oregon public broadcasting 
nine years ago garrett was an unemployed actress she hadnt 
done any television until she filled in for a local talk show host 
who was on maternity leave she interviewed every manner of 
celebrity newsmaker and oddball during that fourmonth stint but 
her favorite guest was rau an affable insurance executive whose 
hobby was antiques 
before the program garrett assembled some props to show how 
easy it was to mistake a very good reproduction for an authentic 
tiffany lamp rau noticed the difference from 100 feet away 
thats a nice reproduction he told her as he gently 
examined the other you know ive got the base for this tiffany 
lamp 
four years later her television career wellestablished 
garrett was looking for a new challenge and she remembered rau 
it had been years since their first meeting but she picked up 
the phone and asked whether hed be interested in doing an 
interview program for antique collectors as it happened rau was 
newly retired and the idea sounded like fun 
the pilot program was straight out of andy hardy like a 
neighborhood troupe doing a talent show garrett produced they 
both starred and an old friend directed there were 24 people in 
the audience counting family members 
from its first airing in 1984 the collectors seemed charmed 
for two days the studio was swamped with postcards and letters 
of praise when the program didnt appear at the same time the 
following sunday the switchboard was flooded with calls garrett 
and rau were clearly on to something 
production began that fall and the first series started in 
janaury 1985 
their next lucky break came midway through the production of 
their third season when oregon public broadcasting hired a new 
executive director maynard orme who had seen some clips of the 
collectors he stopped by the set one day 
the first thing he asked was whats being done to take this 
show national garrett recalls i took one look at him and i 
said youre a collector 
indeed orme had a collection of 1000 model trains 
they submitted a tape to national public broadcasting service 
that fall and were told not to expect any reaction for six to 
eight weeks the positive response came within six days the 
decisionmaker was yet another collector 
each halfhour program has a general theme with several short 
features and interviews with experts in between rau conducts 
spontaneous appraisals of collectibles furnished by a live audience 
although he is astonishing in his knowledge of antiques and 
collectibles of all types rau like all collectors is happiest 
telling about his own specialty 
it began innocently enough with a vinegar cruet handed down 
from his grandmother by 1963 hed assembled a minor collection of 
cruets all in the 3 to 6 range then a fellow offered to sell 
him an art glass piece for 90 
his interest piqued rau began studying about cameo and art 
glass and he began collecting in earnest 
rau learned as one friend put it there was a big difference 
between a vase and a vahzz somehow he was able to make the 
difference plain to his banker who lent him 40000 to invest in 
art glass 
if youre thinking thats a lot of vinegar cruets consider that 
his collection today is worth a cool 1 million 
money however is not the point this is love after all 
happily its there for anybody 
few people can collect rare paintings but signed pieces by 
talented artisans may be a worthwhile investment a sentimental 
display of old toys gathered lovingly over a 30year period may 
also be worth money over time 
if youre willing to spend 200 for an addition to your 
collection youve reached what rau calls an advanced stage of 
acquisition he and garrett agree on some simple ground rules for 
wisely assembling a collection 
first educate your eye read everything you can about your 
subject books price lists and the many good magazines for traders 
next you should get handson experience by going to auctions 
and sales a corollary of the second rule is to leave your 
checkbook at home until you know what theyre doing dont rush 
into it 
the keys to collecting are pride and emotional attachment says 
garrett and she tries to explain the feeling you want it you 
want to live with it you want to put it on the mantle and look at 
it every day 
the third rule is the most important garrett and rau promise if 
you let your heart be your guide you wont be disappointed 
you never regret what you buy says rau youll only 
regret what you dont 
</TEXT>
