opec members are looking to eastern 
europe as a promising crude oil market as the region loosens 
economic ties with the soviet union its dominant supplier to date 
experts predict oil demand will increase as the emerging 
democracies change the centrally planned economies of their former 
communist rulers into freemarket models of the west 
they are going to depend less and less on the soviet union 
iraqi oil minister issam abdul raheem alchalabi said in an 
interview 
they must improve their economy and that means they have 
to consume more energy he said the only way to get that is 
from oil and the only way to get that is from opec countries 
experts say more emphasis may be placed on producing consumer 
goods the auto industry often ignored in the past may be 
targeted for improvement and more cars would lead to greater 
demand for gasoline 
these countries have no other way they must improve their 
consumption said irans oil minister gholamreza aqazadeh 
kuwait plans to set up offices in eastern european capitals 
soviet production shortfalls already have led some nations to turn 
to members of the organization of petroleum exporting countries 
they are certainly starting to become interested said 
joseph stanislaw managing director of cambridge energy research 
associates in paris it is a natural market for opec to go into 
the soviet union the worlds biggest oil producer long has 
been the dominant crude supplier to its eastbloc allies but 
