year of multiyear contracts with several nations 
in negotiating new accords moscow is likely to raise prices and 
demand payment in dollars or other hard currency analysts 
said the east european countries now pay in soviet rubles 
worthless outside the east bloc or by bartering equipment and 
other goods for oil 
once theyre paying in hard currency its a whole new ball 
game said jan vanous research director at planecon a 
washington consulting firm theyll start shopping around 
opec for the first time has a real shot at competing for the 
delivery of oil for domestic consumption he said 
opec secretarygeneral subroto said in a recent interview that a 
hardcurrency requirement would prompt the countries to look for 
convenience which side can supply them at the best price and 
quality 
