fiveyear contracts with wage reductions and 
nostrike clauses are among the concessions united airlines unions 
are offering in their quest to buy parent ual corp for more than 
38 billion 
nonunion employees who would share in the proposed 75 percent 
workers stake also would give up wages and benefits in the event 
of an employee buyout according to documents made public tuesday 
the filings were made by the buyout group with the securities 
and exchange commission in washington 
the group said annual payroll costs for noncontract employees 
would be reduced by 55 million from a 1990 base and reductions 
would remain in effect during the term of labor agreements 
the proposed contracts included in the filings appeared to 
indicate that uniteds three union groups would take 
wageandbenefit cuts of about 10 percent but union spokesmen 
would not confirm the amount of the reduction 
the labor agreements would depend on approval of the buyout by 
ual stockholders the ability of the unions to secure financing and 
ratification of the contracts by the union rankandfile who 
comprise about twothirds of uals work force 
uniteds pilots machinists and flight attendants unions monday 
announced a bid that values ual at more than 38 billion the 
offer is composed of 150 per share in cash 25 per share in debt 
securities and nonvoting common stock in the new company with an 
undetermined value 
