<TEXT>
venezuela and its creditor banks have agreed to 
a plan to reduce about 20 billion of the countrys debt to 
commercial banks 
the agreement in principle provides a boost to the bush 
administrations debtreduction policy the socalled brady plan 
named for treasury secretary nicholas f brady which emphasizes 
reducing existing third world debt rather than making new loans 
venezuela whose 37 billion overall foreign debt is the 
fourthlargest in latin america has fallen behind on its interest 
and capital payments in recent years 
the preliminary pact announced on tuesday covers about 20 
billion of medium and longterm commercial bank debt 
the plan follows a similar agreement signed by creditor banks 
and mexico last month in which banks agreed to cut that countrys 
485 billion debt by some 7 billion the banks were given three 
options reduce debt capital by 35 percent cut interest rates to a 
fixed 625 percent or offer new loans equivalent to 25 percent of 
their oustanding loans to mexico 
under the agreement with venezuela banks have been offered a 
range of options that include permanent debt and debtservice 
reduction a cash buyback of debt and new loans according to 
venezuelan planning minister miguel rodriguez 
negotiations with a representative committee of 16 creditor 
banks are expected to continue until a final package is approved 
rodriguez said he expects to have an agreement with all 300 
creditor banks finalized by july 
robert murphy chairman of the bank committee and a vice 
president at chase manhattan bank said the agreement would be 
attractive to the international financial community 
however neither he nor rodriguez would predict which options 
would prove most popular with the banks they said that until the 
results are in it would be difficult to calculate how much debt 
reduction venezuela would achieve with the package 
the tentative agreement included the following options for 
creditor banks buying back their debt at a reduced 
notyetdetermined price venezuelan debt is currently selling at 
around 40 percent of face value 
exchanging existing debt for new capitalreduced bonds at a 30 
percent discount or interestreduced bonds yielding 675 percent 
providing new money those choosing this option would get two 
series of bonds yielding the london interbank offered rate which 
stands at around 85 percent plus up to 1 percent 
rodriguez said he was hoping for about 1 billion in new money 
