<TEXT>
international trade volume could slow slightly 
this year with inflation and rising interest rates in 
industrialized nations hampering trade expansion the worlds main 
trade forum reported thursday 
experts at the general agreement on tariffs and trade also 
reported that the value of international merchandise trade topped 
3 trillion for the first time in 1989 as the united states 
regained its position from west germany as the worlds top exporter 
gatt experts predicted the volume of goods traded 
internationally would grow by 5 percent to 6 percent in 1990 the 
eighth straight year of expansion 
the value of goods traded on world markets last year rose by 75 
percent from 1988 to 31 trillion the report stated 
the report warned of continuing problems faced by heavily 
indebted countries it also said persistent inflation and rising 
interest rates in industrialized countries threatened to dampen 
business investment an important factor in trade expansion 
in 1989 the united states regained its position as the worlds 
leading exporter after three years in second place behind west 
germany the report said 
us exports were worth some 3644 billion ahead of west 
germanys 3414 billion and japans 2752 billion us imports 
totalled 4920 billion compared to west germanys 2698 billion 
and japans 2108 billion 
the report said the value of us exports rose 95 percent during 
the decade while imports shot up 120 percent this compared with a 
world average increase of 86 percent for both imports and exports 
canada had the most significant growth among the biggest trading 
nations moving from 10th to seventh place in the rankings 
canadian exports and imports in 1989 each totaled about 120 
billion respective increases of 107 percent and 112 percent over 
1979 
in contrast to growth in most other areas of the world east 
europe and the soviet union witnessed stagnation and even decline 
in trade last year according to initial estimates cited by gatt 
it said the combined value of imports and exports rose only 1 
percent in the soviet union hungarys merchandise trade contracted 
by 3 percent and bulgarias by 4 percent 
the value of polands trade rose 7 percent because of a surge in 
imports czechoslovakias imports and exports increased by 4 
percent east germanys by 25 percent and romanias by 05 
percent the report said 
even though growth in the overall volume of world trade was 
expected to slow down in 1990 it would still exceed forecast 
output growth of about 3 percent the report said 
looking ahead it said the level and pattern of world trade 
would be affected as east europe and the soviet union increased 
trade with countries outside the region necessary plant and 
infrastructure investments as part of the process of economic 
reform would call for higher imports of capital equipment and 
business services 
traditionally about 60 percent of soviet and east european 
exports and imports have been traded within the region the report 
said 
bulgaria czechoslovakia and east germany have relied most 
heavily on soviet bloc trading partners while poland hungary the 
soviet union and romania sent close to half their merchandise 
exports to countries outside the region 
citing figures for 1988 the report said west european sales to 
the soviet bloc totalled 429 billion while imports from the 
soviet bloc amounted to 461 billion 
it said us trade with east europe and the soviet union 
remained small in 1988 us exports to the region totalled less 
than 5 billion and purchases from these countries less than 3 
billion 
gatt is a marketoriented trade forum that draws up agreements 
to liberalize world trade its 96 members account for more than 
fourfifths of global commerce 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

