<TEXT>
japanese investment houses said wednesday they 
temporarily had stopped underwriting new issues of stocks bonds 
and warrants in an attempt to limit risks to investors until the 
sinking tokyo stock market stabilizes 
the unprecedented move which affects capitalraising efforts by 
japanese companies at home and overseas follows a nearly 21 
percent drop so far this year in the tokyo stock exchanges 
225issue nikkei stock average 
securities companies agreed tuesday to halt underwriting of new 
convertible bonds warrants and common stocks for at least one 
month nobuo kurakazu director of the securities division at daiwa 
securities co told the associated press 
many issues have already fallen below 100 yen 65 us cents 
which is abnormal he said 
hiroshi tanaka chief of the underwriting division at yamaichi 
securities co said we can no longer continue normal sales 
activities under the current market situation where prices of 
stocks and bonds have kept sinking 
it is best to halt the sales rather than keep selling those 
bonds when nobody is interested he said adding that demand for 
company bonds had been affected especially hard 
by stopping the flow of additional shares into the market the 
halt also could help prevent further weakening of prices caused by 
dilution 
japans financial markets were closed wednesday for the spring 
equinox holiday 
on monday the nikkei plunged 135320 points or 415 percent 
its thirdlargest daily fall ever it tumbled another 45605 
points or 148 percent on tuesday to 3080719 the lowest since 
it closed at 3067839 on jan 9 1989 
the total value of securities listed on the tokyo exchange has 
diminished by almost 600 billion this year to 33 trillion by 
last friday 
kurakazu said the decision to halt underwriting followed the 
tokyo markets continuing plunges and uncertainty surrounding 
tuesdays discount rate increase 
the bank of japan raised its official discount rate the key 
lending rate to commercial banks by 1 percentage point to 525 
percent in an effort to stem inflation and restabilize financial 
markets 
analysts said the bank was slow in raising the rate they said 
the delay contributed to the plunge of the yen and stock and bond 
prices prompting many companies to give up plans for raising 
capital 
mitsukoshi yasuda trust and banking co and the bank of 
miyazaki recently have canceled plans to raise capital by issuing 
new common stock 
