<TEXT>
a judge today barred federal regulators from 
seizing an ailing illinois thrift institution on the grounds the 
chief regulator had been unconstitutionally appointed 
the decision could derail the governments massive savings and 
loan bailout 
us district judge royce c lamberth ordered the treasury 
departments office of thrift supervision not to take over olympic 
federal savings and loan association berwyn ill until a new 
chief regulator is constitutionally installed in office 
royce ruled that both salvatore r martoche director of the 
office and his immediate predecessor m danny wall were 
unconstitutionally appointed 
under the bailout law wall inherited his office automatically 
when the predecessor agency he headed was abolished 
olympic argued this inheritance of office violated the 
constitutional provision that the president shall appoint with the 
advice and consent of the senate all officers of the united 
states 
michael robinson a spokesman for the justice department said 
the government asked the judge to stay his order and would appeal 
the ruling 
regulators had not moved to take over olympic but the thrift 
believed it was in imminent danger of seizure lamberths decision 
could dramatically delay the seizure of some 200 other thrifts 
believed close to failure 
though the ruling applies only to olympic it also calls into 
question the legality of the takeover of 137 thrifts with 97 
billion in assets since last aug 9 when president bush signed 
the bailout law 
the ruling likely would not affect the 265 sampls seized before 
aug 9 when wall was the constitutionally appointed chairman of 
the now defunct federal home loan bank board 
