<TEXT>
somewhere out in the dim future a new stock 
market fad is developing waiting to be discovered and exploited 
you may be sure it will be too because the stock market needs 
stories call it excitement to generate inout trading the kind 
that produces the commissions that support the industry 
like astronomers scanning the heavens the investment 
researchers are seeking a star something to generate as much 
activity as the old takeover and junk bond crazes that seem to have 
burned out 
whatever they find will be seized upon by opportunists new 
moneymaking geniuses will be presented to the investing public 
new faces will grace the magazine covers drama will be pumped into 
a dull market 
sudden wealth will parade again and the new stars will shine 
bright theyll offer ways of doing things thatll make 1980s stars 
look like coal theyll offer new concepts and visions theyll 
scorn the old way 
nothing is certain about the future of course but if history 
means very much the expectation just described has a very good 
chance of becoming the reality it has happened over and over so 
why not again 
so many fads have come and gone they could fill a garbage truck 
fast food conglomerates real estate construction natural 
resources south african mining gold energy recessionproof 
stocks and inflationproof stocks 
there was a time when any company with a hardsounding name 
with a k or an x or a z in it was examined as a hightech 
highflyer possibility there was a time when cashrich companies 
were simply takeover possibilities 
every month or so throughout the past 20 years there has been a 
new mutual fund created to seize upon fads within fads someone 
right now for instance is probably hatching a peace dividend fund 
most of the fads just faded 
the rage over fast food stocks diminished after so it seems 
every hamlet in america was inhabited by a hamburger or fried 
chicken outlet and growth thereafter was based on such things as 
service and profits 
the frantic search for companies with hightech names lost its 
appeal when it was discovered that the names had to be accompanied 
by hightech products or the stocks were worth hardly a dime some 
werent 
but as many people recall a lot of the fads went out with a 
blast 
the rush to conglomerate stocks was one of the strongest of all 
movements and it was supported by an outpouring of scholarly 
research much of which concluded that one and one equaled three 
the word synergy came into popular usage otherwise intelligent 
chief executive officers explained to shareholders that the 
acquisition of another company wouldnt just add new revenues but 
would enhance existing ones 
wall street bought the idea and in turn so did the public and 
conglomerates assumed some of the biggest priceearnings ratios 
ever seen in this century the public fed them money and they 
bought even more companies 
then the public discovered that synergism wasnt always there 
that one and one didnt make three that earnings werent enhanced 
and that in some cases the company had no reason for existence 
except to buy other companies 
a couple of conglomerate bankruptcies then caught their 
attention and sadly and probably not wiser they they returned to 
the old mathematics 
the biggest blast of all of course may be the most recent the 
collapse of the junk bond market and the slowing of the takeover 
frenzy in dollar terms it most certainly is the biggest collapse 
of any of the fads 
based on recent history however this collapse is no reason for 
an end to fads the shortterm mentality the greed the urgency of 
the kill still pervade the market 
nobody can say what the new fad will be but you wont have to 
wait long with the geography economics and politics of the world 
rearranged in the last few years the possibilities are many 
how about russian stocks 
</TEXT>
