<TEXT>
the chairman of a senate subcommittee that 
oversees the securities and exchange commission said wednesday he 
is willing to add a curb on program trading to pending legislation 
sen christopher dodd dconn also said he favors giving the 
sec authority to regulate stockindex futures 
legislation that would give the sec new powers to halt trading 
in emergencies and keep tabs on the financial health of brokerage 
houses parent companies is awaiting floor action in both the house 
and senate 
but the house version contains a provision allowing the sec to 
restrain program trading the computerized trading of large blocks 
of stocks based on price differences between the securities and 
stockindex futures markets the senate version does not 
dodd said that after talking with sec chairman richard c 
breeden who did not seek but says he can live with the program 
trading amendement if thats the case then we can either add 
something on the floor as a floor amendment or wait until 
conference with the house on a final verison of a bill 
dodd chairman of the senate banking committees subcommittee on 
securities said he doesnt want to dismember the commodity 
futures trading commission which currently oversees stockindex 
futures 
rather he told a news conference in his senate office my 
inclination is to be supportive of taking stockindex futures and 
moving them over under the jurisdiction of the sec 
dodd conceded that such a move would meet opposition by 
congressional supporters of the cftc which is under the control of 
house and senate agriculture committees 
while from a theoretical standpoint it has made some sense to 
me to move in that direction our job now is that the committee 
must examine the practicalities of that dodd said 
stockindex futures are financial products that allow investors 
to speculate on stock indexes such as the standard amp poors 500 
without buying the underlying stocks 
the senate banking committee has scheduled a hearing next week 
on which federal agency should set minimum standards for margins 
the down payments investors must make to purchase securities or 
futures on credit 
the federal reserve now sets margins for the stock markets while 
the futures exchanges themselves set margins in their industry 
critics argue that wide disparities between securities and 
futures margins have caused or least worsened heavy trading in 
stockindex futures some people believe the disparity causes sharp 
price fluctuations in the markets 
witnesses at the march 29 hearing are scheduled to include sec 
chairman richard c breeden and cftc chairman wendy gramm as well 
as fed chairman alan greenspan 
some house members are exploring possible legislation to merge 
both agencies into one super agency dodd called that plan an 
interesting discussion but i certainly havent drawn any conclusion 
that it makes any sense at all 
</TEXT>
