<TEXT>
western union co told federal 
regulators wednesday it may have to seek bankruptcy court 
protection if it cannot meet mounting debt interest payments 
in a filing with the securities and exchange commission western 
union said if it cannot raise additional funds it probably will 
not be able to make 51 million in interest payments on 530 
million in outstanding notes due june 15 
the notes which carry interest rates of 1925 percent and 16 
percent are due to mature june 15 1991 failure to meet interest 
payments would result in default 
western union also said in the filing that the sec is conducting 
an inquiry into the timing of writedowns against company earnings 
in the first quarter of 1988 western union said it is cooperating 
with the inquiry 
company spokesman warren bechtel said the sec has questioned 
actions leading up to the restructuring charge which he said took 
place under previous management 
bechtel also said that as part of its agreement with us trust 
co of new york the trustee overseeing the 1925 percent notes 
western unions consolidated capital must not fall below a certain 
level 
if that requirement is not met for two consecutive quarters 
western union must repurchase 100 million of worth of its 
outstanding notes he said 
western union told the sec it could fall below the preordained 
level by march 31 the end of the first quarter 
but its just a possiblity down the road bechtel said 
its not something that exists 
bechtel said the company wants to restructure its debt before 
the june 15 deadline on the 51 million in interest payments 48 
million on 500 million in 1925 percent notes and 3 million on 
the 16 percent notes the payments are due twice a year 
western union said in the filing it may offer to exchange the 
notes for new securities with lower interest rates and longer 
repayment schedules 
if it cannot restructure western union may use the options of 
raising money through a public offering of stock or by selling its 
assets quickly the company said in the filing 
without the restructuring the company could default and that 
could force western union to seek protection under the us 
bankruptcy code the company said 
western union took special charges of 603 million in the 1988 
first quarter connected with the planned unloading of the companys 
microwave voiceswitching facilities 
western union has exited the business of providing 
communications facilities to focus on specialized business and 
consumer services but the company has continued to struggle 
reporting 32 million in losses in 1989 
