shawmut national corp revised its 1989 earnings 
to show a 1289 million loss after federal regulators found the 
banks reserves for losses from real estate loans were inadequate 
according to a published report thursday 
shawmut one of new englands largest banking companies in 
january reported a profit of 2017 million for last year 
more than 170 federal bank examiners spent six weeks studying 
the banks records before the company decided that its reserves to 
protect against bad real estate loans were too small the new york 
times reported 
the move was the latest sign that the government is being more 
critical than usual in judging bank real estate loans examinations 
of real estate lending led to a 11 billion loss at bank of new 
england corp earlier this year 
after the review shawmut which is based in boston and hartford 
and has more than 400 branches nearly doubled the size of its 
reserves for loan losses at the end of 1989 to 739 million from 
383 million the times said 
increases in loan loss reserves are subtracted from earnings or 
from capital in the case of a loss the banks nonperforming loans 
which are not paying interest or face other troubles rose to 
1045 billion from 5356 million 
the bank was surprised by the federal examiners findings the 
newspaper said shawmut had increased its reserves to cover losses 
on real estate loans for commercial projects eliminating almost 
all of its fourthquarter profits 
